column168: 2.0 SITE BACKGROUND AND HISTORY.  THE SITE IS LOCATED ON THE NORTH SIDE OF THE WESTBOUND LANE OF I-90/94 (KENNEDY EXPRESSWAY) IMMEDIATELY EAST OF AND UNDER THE SOUTH ABUTMENT AND SLOPEWALL OF THE KIMBALL AVENUE VIADUCT.  AT APPROXIMATELY 03:40 ON JUNE 9, 2005, A TANKER TRUCK OVERTURNED AT THE OUTBOUND (WESTBOUND) EXIT 45B (KIMBALL AVENUE) OF THE KENNEDY EXPRESSWAY.  THE TANKER WAS TRANSPORTING APPROXIMATELY 6,100 GALLONS OF DGME.  UPON OVERTURNING, THE TANKER TRAILER HIT THE EAST CONCRETE BARRIER WALL OF WESTBOUND I-90/94 AT APPROXIMATELY STATION 360+00.  THE TANKER TRAILER SEPARATED FROM THE TRACTOR AND MOUNTED THE BARRIER WALL, SLIDING ALONG THE TOP OF THE BARRIER WALL PRIOR TO IMPACTING THE STEEL COLUMN SUPPORTING THE OVERHEAD SIGN LOCATED AT STATION 363+29.  AFTER SLIDING THE TRACTOR CAME TO REST IN THE EASTERN TRAFFIC LANE, NEAR THE TANKER TRAILER.  BOTH DIESEL SADDLE TANKS OF THE TRACTOR WERE INTACT.  FIGURE 3 INDICATES THE APPROXIMATE POSITIONS OF THE TRACTOR AND TRAILER SUBSEQUENT TO THE INCIDENT, AS WELL AS THE LANDSCAPED AREAS AND INFRASTRUCTURE DAMAGED AS A RESULT OF THE INCIDENT (DESCRIBED BELOW).  UPON IMPACTING THE SIGN SUPPORT COLUMN, THE TANKER RUPTURED AND SPLIT INTO TWO PORTIONS, RELEASING THE TANKER CONTENTS, A PORTION OF WHICH IGNITED.  THE PORTION OF THE DGME THAT DID NOT IGNITE WAS RELEASED TO THE EASTERN EMERGENCY LANE (SHOULDER), WHERE IT WAS ABLE TO ENTER A STORM SEWER INLET LOCATED APPROXIMATELY AT STATION 361+00.  THE STORM SEWER INLET AT 361+00 DISCHARGED TO A CULVERT OUTFALL ALONG THE RIGHT-OF-WAY (ROW) EMBANKMENT.  THE DGME FLOWING FROM THE CULVERT OUTFALL IMPACTED SOIL ALONG THE DRAINAGE SWALE THAT IN TURN DISCHARGED TO A STORM SEWER CATCH BASIN LOCATED IN THE GRASS AREA ADJACENT TO THE ACCIDENT INVESTIGATION AREA PRESENT ALONG THE WEST SIDE OF THE KIMBALL AVENUE OFF-RAMP.  AN UNKNOWN AMOUNT OF BURNING DGME WAS RELEASED TO THE ROW EMBANKMENT THROUGH SEAMS, JOINTS, AND CRACKS IN AND UNDER THE CONCRETE BARRIER WALL, WITH THE MOST EXTREME BURNING OCCURRING IMMEDIATELY WEST OF THE SIGN SUPPORT COLUMN AT STATION 363+29 TO THE BRIDGE ABUTMENT LOCATED AT STATION 364+07.  SEVERAL TREES WERE CHARRED IN THE BURN AREA WERE DAMAGED BY FLAMES, HEAT AND DGME EXPOSURE.  APPROXIMATELY 9,500 SQUARE FEET OF LANDSCAPED AREA WAS BURNED AS A RESULT OF THE INCIDENT.  A PORTION OF THE BURNING DGME RAN DOWN THE CONCRETE WALKWAY ADJACENT TO THE VIADUCT AND APPARENTLY ACCUMULATED UNDER THE NORTHEAST CORNER OF THE KIMBALL AVENUE VIADUCT, CHARRING THE NORTHERNMOST ELASTOMERIC BRIDGE BEARINGS, BURNING PAINT FROM THE STEEL FRAMING OF TWO BEAMS AND THE HEADWALL, AND REPORTEDLY DAMAGING FIBER OPTIC CABLE LOCATED IN A JUNCTION BOX AND CONDUIT MOUNTED TO THE NORTH SIDE OF THE CONCRETE BARRIER WALL IMMEDIATELY EAST OF THE BRIDGE ABUTMENT.  ADDITIONAL INTRASTRUCTURE DAMAGED AS A RESULT OF THE INCIDENT INCLUDES JOINT FILLER BETWEEN THE CONCRETE BARRIER WELL EXPANSION JOINTS (WHICH BURNED IN THE FIRE), THE FOUNDATION TO THE OVERHEAD SIGN STRUCTURE HIT B
column169: 2.1 PREVIOUS REMEDIAL ACTION AND INVESTIGATION.  SIGNIFICANT PROCESS ON CLEANUP AND RESTORATION EFFORTS HAS BEEN ACHIEVED TO DATE:  PRESSURE WASHING OF THE TRACTOR AND TRAILER STAGING AREA IN THE ACCIDENT INVESTIGATION AREA ADJACENT TO THE KIMBALL AVENUE OFF-RAMP; PRESSURE WASHING OF THE BRIDGE ABUTMENT, BRIDGE BUSHING, STEEL BRIDGE FRAME, SLOPEWALL, CONCRETE DRAINAGE SWALE AT THE TOE OF THE SLOPEWALL AND EAST KIMBALL AVENUE SIDEWALK AND GUTTER;  PRESSURE WASHING OF THE EXTERIOR I-90/94 SHOULDER (EMERGENCY LANE) ALONG THE SPILL AREA; COLLECTION OF ALL PRESSURE WASHING WASTEWATER USING A VACUUM TRUCK; COLLECTION OF THE IMPACTED LIQUID ACCUMULATED IN THE AFFECTED STORM STRUCTURES USING A VACUUM TRUCK;  DISPOSAL OF THE COLLECTED WASTEWATER AND IMPACTED LIQUID AT THE INDUSTRIAL WASTE SERVICES FACILITY IN CHICAGO, ILLINOIS;  REPLACEMENT OF THE LIGHT POLE BY MEADE ELECTRIC COMPANY OF MCCOOK, ILLINOIS;  UNDERGROUND UTILITY LOCATING FOR THE SITE; REMOVAL OF IMPACTED SEDIMENT FROM THE STORM SEWER INLET AND CULVERT STRUCTURE APPROXIMATELY LOCATED AT STATION 31+00 BY PRESSURE WASHING AND COLLECTION OF WASTEWATER GENERATED DURING THE CLEANING; CONDUCTING A SITE SURVEY OF TOPOGRAPHY, STRUCTURES, AND LANDSCAPE FEATURES;  REMOVAL AND CHIPPING OF TREES DAMAGED BY THE FIRE; PRELIMINARY INVESTIGATION OF THE BURN AREA, IMPACTED SWALE, AND PERIMETER OF THE BURN AREA BY ADVANCING HAND AUGERS ANE EXVACATION OF TEST PITS, COLLECTING SOIL SAMPLES AND CONDUCTING HEADSCAPE SCREENING OF THE SOIL SAMPLES AND CONDUCTING HEADSCAPE SCREENING OF THE SOIL SAMPLES FOR VOLATILE CONSTITUENTS USING A PID;  EXCAVATION OF IMPACTED SOIL ALONG THE DRAINAGE SWALE ADJACENT TO THE ACCIDENT INVESTIGATION AREA AND LOADING EXCAVATED SOIL INTO ROLL-OFF BOXES FOR UPCOMING OFF-SITE DISPOSAL AT THE WASTE MANAGEMENT, INC. (WMI) COUNTRYSIDE LANDFILL IN GRAYSLAKE, ILLINOIS;  COLLECTION OF CONFIRMATION SOIL SAMPLES FRO THE EXCAVATED SWALE; INITIATED EXCAVATION OF IMPACTED SOIL ALONG THE WEST END OF THE BURN AREA;  REMOVAL OF THE DAMAGED "WGN STUDIOS" SIGN;  CONDUCTING A STRUCTURAL ASSESSMENT OF THE INFRASTUCTURE DAMAGED BY THE INCIDENT; AND PHOTOGRAPHIC DOCUMENTATION OF IMPACTED AREA, DAMAGED INFRASTRUCTURE AND OTHER RELEVANT SITE FEATURES.

column168: Driver slowing and changing lanes. He intended to make a left turn approximately 1/4 mile ahead. The roadway has a slight down grade and makes a gradual curve to the right. Driver alleges he looked down at his gauges and when he looked up he had made contact with the concrete divider in the center of the roadway. He overcorrected causing a sudden shift in the liquid. The tractor and trailer overturned on top of the concrete divider. The shell of the cargo tank was punctured on impact. Highway patrol was called by passing motorist. Highway patrol and fire department arrived at the scene. One puncture was located near the center of the tank at the read and one puncture was located near the center of the tank mid center. The release lasted about 4 hours. The cargo tank and tractor were uprighted by a local wrecker service and removed from the scene. Spill Center was notified and they made the necessary notifications to all related agencies. Driver was not injured. Carrier safety personnel arrived to assist in the recovery.
column169: This driver received comprehensive training on rollover prevention during his orientation two months prior to this accident.    Our next company newsletter will include an article about distracted drivers.    We have also published a payroll stuffer about rollover prevention.

column168: THE DRIVER PULLED INTO THE STATION TO UNLOAD PRODUCT.  HE SET THE BRAKES WHILE HE WAITED FOR A CAR TO MOVE.  AFTER THE CAR MOVED HE FINISHED SPOTTING THE TRUCK TO UNLOAD, BUT THIS TIME HE FORGOT TO SET THE BRAKES.  HE PROCEEDED TO UNLOAD, FIRST THE TRUCK WAS TRANSFERRED THEN HE BEGAN TO TRANSFER THE TRAILER.  WHILE UNLOADING THE FIRST COMPARTMENT OF THE TRAILER THE TRUCK BEGAN TO ROLL BACKWARDS.  THE DRIVER RAN TO THE CAB, OPENED THE DOOR AND SET THE BRAKES THEN RAN BACK TO THE TRAILER TO SHUT THE DELIVERY VALVE.  THE TRUCK HAD ROLLED OVER THE DELIVERY HOSES AND TORN THEM FROM THEIR FITTINGS RELEASING PRODUCT.  THE DRIVER TOOK CHARGE AND BLOCKED THE PRODUCT AS BEST HE COULD FROM ENTERING THE STORM DRAIN.  STATION PERSONNEL SHUT DOWN THE DISPENSERS AND CALLED THE FIRE DEPARTMENT.  THE RELEASE LASTED LESS THAN 30 SECONDS.  A CONTRACTOR WAS CALLED IN TO HANDLE THE CLEAN UP UNDER THE DIRECTION OF COUNTY HEALTH INSPECTORS AND BENETO'S EMERGENCY RESPONSE TEAM.
column169: A DETAILED ANALYSIS THAT ADDRESSES THE ROOT CAUSE OF THIS INCIDENT WILL BE SHARED WITH ALL OUR DRIVERS THRU SAFETY BULLETINS, TAILGATE MEETINGS AND DURING THE NEXT ROUND OF SAFETY MEETINGS.  ALSO A PROCEDURE CHANGE HAS BEEN IMPLEMENTED FOR CARGO DELIVERY.  CAB DOORS WILL REMAIN UNLOCKED ON THE SIDE OF THE TRUCK IN WHICH THE DELIVERY IS TAKING PLACE.

column168: DRIVER WAS UNLOADING AT A MURPHY STATION AND HAD UNLOADING AREA BARRICADED OFF USING CONES TO PREVENT OTHER MOTORISTS FROM ENTERING THE AREA.  PASSENGER VEHICLE WENT THROUGH CONES AND RAN OVER HOSES AND FITTINGS, COMING TO A REST ON TOP OF A FITTING, BREAKING DROP FITTING LOOSE FROM GROUND CONNECTION AND CREATING A NO-LEAD SPILL.  PASSENGER VEHICLE BECAME STUCK ON TOP OF FITTING AND COULDN'T MOVE.  DRIVER QUICKLY SHUT OFF PRODUCT FLOW, AVOIDING A LARGER SPILL.  LAKELAND FIRE DEPARTMENT ARRIVED AND ASSISTED WITH CLEAN UP.
column169: ENCOURAGE THE MEDIC TO DO MORE SPECIAL REPORTS ON THE DANGERS OF ENTERING AN AREA WHERE FUEL IS BEING UNLOADED TO ENCOURAGE SAFER DRIVING HABITS AND CREATING A BETTER SENSE OF AWARENESS AMONG THE GENERAL PUBLIC.

column168: On June 27, 2005 an Onyx employee was loading a hazardous materials shipment at the Onyx 10-day intransit facility located in Latham, NY.  While performing a final inspection of the shipment, it was discovered that a 55-gallon drum containing an acetone/osmium tetroxide flammable liquid toxic mixture was leaking.  Approximately 1 gallon of the material had leaked through holes on the side of the drum onto the floor of the trailer.  The leaking drum was overpacked into an 85-gallon drum.  The material that had leaked onto the floor of the trailer was cleaned up with speedi-dry and absorbant pads.  The cleanup materials were placed into the 85-gallon overpack along with the leaking drum for disposal.
column169: It was determined this spill was caused due to poor integrity of the 55-gallon drum.  In the future, composite poly lined steel (6HA) drums will be used for this material.  Although the 55 gallon drum used for this shipment was not incompatible, 6HA drums will be used in the future to lessen the risk of future incidents.

column168: SHIPMENT DID NOT HAVE THE PROPER DUNNAGE AROUND PALLET.  WHEN OTHER PALLETS WERE LOADED BEHIND FROM ORIGIN SERVICE CENTER, FORK BLADE PUNCTURED A BOX AND 1 CAN (PINT) OF ADHESIVE.  WHEN FREIGHT WAS BEING UNLOADED HERE IN SACRAMENTO, WE NOTICED ADHESIVE SPILLED ON TRAILER FLOOR.  NO DRY SWEEP WAS NEEDED AS ADHESIVE WAS ALREADY DRY ON TRAILER FLOOR.  WE SCRAPED UP DRY GLUE AND ORIGINAL CAN AND DISPOSED PROPERLY.
column169: WE SENT MESSAGE TO ORIGIN SERVICE CENTER MANAGER TO REVIEW WITH HIS CREW ON HOW PROPER USE OF DUNNAGE COULD HAVE PREVENTED SUCH A SPILL.  WE ALSO USED IN OUR DOCK MEETINGS TO TEACH OUR DOCK WORKERS WHAT CAN HAPPEN IF DUNNAGE IS NOT PROPERLY USED WHEN LOADING LIQUIDS.

column168: A WESTBOUND BNSF TRAIN TRAVERSED A BROKEN RAIL (DETAILED FRACTURE) IN THE MAIN TRACK AND SUBSEQUENTLY DERAILED 43 RAILCARS IN A PILE AT A MAIN TRACK SWITCH THREE MILES FURTHER WEST OF THE BROKEN RAIL.  XOMX 310006, A TWO COMPARTMENT TANK CAR, DERAILED ON ITS SIDE AND PRODUCT LEAKED FROM BOTH MANWAYS INTO A GROUND DEPRESSION DIRECTLY UNDER THE MANWAY AREA.  THE MANWAY SECUREMENT BOLTS WERE CHECKED AND FOUND TO BE TOOL TIGHT.  XOMX 310006 WAS UP - RIGHTED, STOPPING FURTHER PRODUCT RELEASE.  THE REMAINING PRODUCTS IN XOMX 310006 WERE TRANSFERRED INTO TANKER TRUCKS ON 6/14/05 WITHOUT FURTHER INCIDENT.  THE MANWAY GASKETS WERE INSPECTED AND FOUND TO BE IN PLACE AND BOTH APPEARED TO BE IN GOOD CONDITION.  A BNSF ENVIRONMENTAL CONTRACTOR REMEDIATED SPILLED PRODUCT THAT POOLED IN THE DEPRESSION AND EXCAVATED IMPACTED SOIL.  THE EXCAVATED SOIL WAS STOCKPILED ON PLASTIC SHEETING PENDING FURTHER ANALYSIS AND APPROPRIATE DISPOSAL.

column168: RPBX 23506 WAS REPORTED IN RAILYARD LEAKING PRODUCT FROM THE TOP FITTINGS OF THIS TANK CAR AND IT WAS CORDONED OFF IN THE RAILYARD.  BNSF RESPONDER FOUND NO SEAL AT THE PROTECTIVE HOUSING COVER AND THE LIQUID VALVE CLOSURE CAP WAS LOOSE.  THE CAP'S SECUREMENT CHAIN RING WAS BENT AND THE CHAIN WAS BINDING.  RESPONDER ADJUSTED THE RING AND AFTERWARDS WAS ABLE TO TOOL TIGHTEN THE CLOSURE CAP.  RESPONDER ALSO FOUND ALL FOUR FILL HOLE SECUREMENT BOLTS WERE SLIGHTLY MORE THAN HAND TIGHT AND THESE WERE TOOL TIGHTENED.  AFTER SECUREMENT WAS FINALIZED NO FURTHER PRODUCT RELEASE WAS EVIDENT.  LATER, INTERNAL PRESSURE WAS REDUCED BY LOOSENING FILL HOLE BOLTS FOR RESPONDER TO CHECK OUTAGE LEVEL.  OUTAGE WAS OBSERVED AT THE BOTTOM LIP OF THE FILL HOLE NOZZLE, I.E., NO APPARENT OUTAGE.  TEMPERATURE AT THIS TIME WAS 71 DEGREES F.  RESPONDER CONTACTED SHIPPER AND SHIPPER REPRESENTATIVE ASSERTED THAT RPBX 23506 HAD THE PROPER OUTAGE AFTER BEING LOADED.  ON 6/14, SHIPPER SENT A REPRESENTATIVE TO BARSTOW AND AT 2010 HRS. PDT, THE OUTAGE LEVEL WAS CHECKED AND IT WAS NOW APPROXIMATELY NINE INCHES BELOW THE NOZZLE NECK, AS PRODUCT EXPANSION HAD EBBED.  AS NO FURTHER PRODUCT RELEASE EVIDENT AFTER TANK CAR WAS RESECURED, RPBX 23506 WAS RELEASED TO PROCEED TO DESTINATION.  PRODUCT THAT IMPACTED THE GROUND WAS NEUTRALIZED.

INSPECTION REVEALED NO BLOCKING AND BRACING IN THIS LOAD TO PREVENT ANY LATERAL OR LONGITUDINAL LOAD SHIFTS.  LOAD CONSISTED OF TWO SINGLE ROWS OF WOVEN PLASTIC SUPER SACK TOTE BAGS.  ONE BAG AT THE REAR FELL OVER INTO THE VOID AT THE DOORWAY SPILLING CONTENTS FROM A TOP TEAR IN THE FALLEN BAG.  BAG WAS REPAIRED AND RETURNED TO THE LOAD.  BEADS THAT FELL ONTO THE PAVEMENT AND THAT SPILLED INSIDE THE CONTAINER WERE SWEPT UP FOR LATER APPROPRIATE DISPOSAL.  LADING WAS ADJUSTED WITH THE TWO REAR BAGS NOW BANDED ON WOODEN PALLETS WITH FLOOR BRACING APPLIED.

column42: PAINT INCLUDING PAINT, LACQUER, ENAMEL, STAIN, SHELLAC SOLUTIONS, VARNISH, POLISH, LIQUID FILLER AND LIQUID LACQUER BASE
column168: ON JUNE 8, 2005, OUR TRUCK LEFT GARLAND, TEXAS LOADED WITH PAINT RESIN, 11 TOTES AND 3 55 GALLON DRUMS, IN ROUTE TO HOUSTON.  AT APPROXIMATELY 7:30 P.M. OUR TRUCK WAS TRAVELING SOUTH ON HIGHWAY 59 AT THE I-10 INTERCHANGE.  OUR TRUCK MOVED INTO THE RIGHT EXIT LANE FOR I-10 EAST AT APPROXIMATELY 20 MPH, WHEN ANOTHER VEHICLE ACCELERATED AROUND THE LEFT SIDE OF OUR TRUCK IN ORDER TO PASS.  THIS LANE STARTS OUT WIDE AND TAPERS INTO THE CURVED PORTION OF THE ROADWAY.  HOWEVER, THIS IS A SINGLE LANE EXIT RAMP.  UPON PASSING OUR VEHICLE, THE ADVERSE VEHICLE SLAMMED ON HIS BRAKES AND CAUSED OUR DRIVER TO STEER SHARP TO THE RIGHT, CAUSING OUR VEHICLE TO STRIKE THE BARRIER.  UPON STRIKING THE BARRIER, OUR DRIVER LOST CONTROL AND OUR VEHICLE FLIPPING IT ON ITS SIDE.  OUR VEHICLE THEN SLID DOWN THE EXIT RAMP ON IT'S SIDE UNTIL IT CAME TO A STOP.  THE ADVERSE VEHICLE DID NOT STOP.  THE DRIVER THEN EXITED OUR VEHICLE THROUGH THE WINDSHIELD AND CALLED OUR COMPANY ON HIS HANDHELD RADIO.  911 WAS CALLED AND HFD AND EMS, ALONG WITH HPD CAME IMMEDIATELY TO THE SCENE.  THE HOUSTON FIRE DEPARTMENT CONTAINED THE SPILL UNTIL GARNER ENVIRONMENTAL ARRIVED.  THE SPILL WAS IMMEDIATELY CONTAINED, THE TRUCK WAS UP-RIGHTED AND REMOVED AT OUR FACILITY FOR FURTHER CLEANUP BY GARNER ENVIRONMENTAL.
column169: OUR COMPANY HAS SAFETY MEETINGS ON A MONTHLY BASIS.  HAZMAT TRAINING IS DONE AT LEAST TWICE YEARLY.  TRAINING IS ALSO GIVEN TO ALL NEW DRIVER'S WHEN HIRED.  "ACCIDENT FREE DRIVING" AND THE "SMITH SYSTEM" ARE GIVEN TO ALL DRIVERS DURING THE YEAR (I BELIVE TRAINING SHOULD BE GIVEN TO 4 WHEELER'S IN REGARDS TO CUTTING OFF COMMERCIAL VEHICLES) TRAINING WILL CONTINUE WITH EMPHASIS ON HAULING HAZMAT SAFETY.

column168: Customer's employee was relocating tank. While moving from one field to another, he made a left turn from Geer Road to Alderson Road and rolled tank. Responsible party called9-1-1. Responding agencies--County FD, CHP, Haz-mat unit from Stanislaus County Dept of Env. Resources were dispatched. A company rep was also sent to the scene. A liquid valve on top of the tank was sheared off.Tank was on its side with vapor leaking from sheared valve. Tank was relocated approx. 50 yards to the east to nprevent downwind exposure. Tank was then uuprighted and vapor valve was opened to release pressure from tank and prevent liquid release. However, liquid was released which vaporized upon atmospheric exposure. Internal valve failed to completely close at sheared valve.Due to risks of attempting to stop leak and the lack of downwind exposure considerations. Vapor contined to be released from the tank for approx. 5 hours. Approx. 750 gallons of water were used to shield personnel while opening vapor valves and to direct vapor cloud from time to time. All incident operations were approved by the IC (CHP Officer Jerry Kessler #10715).
column169: Drivers need to slow down while towing equipment; remind all customers that ammonia regulators need to be removed from valves during transit; label tanks re; removal of regulators from valves during transit. On March 30, 2005, Stanislaus Farm Supply hosted an ammonia training for employees, customers, local fire departments, and Stanislaus County Department of Environmental Resources haz-mat team. I believe that this training was very helpful at this incident. Stanislaus Farm Supply will continue to help train local responders, employees and customers in the safe handling of ammonia products. Cal-Ammonia (Stockton, CA) has played a hughe role in this training. We will continue to work together to educate surrounding counties and their responders on safe ammonia handling and emergency response procedures.

column168: SHIPMENT OF 3 TOTES WITH 300 GALLONS EACH AND TOTAL WEIGHT OF 8844 LBS WAS LOADED ON A DELIVERY TRAILER AT THE SERVICE CENTER IN BENICIA, CA.  THE DRIVER LEFT THE SERVICE CENTER AND MADE SIX OTHER DELIVERIES IN ANTIOCH, CA. BEFORE HEADING FOR HIS LAST DELIVERY OF THE 3 TOTES OF G-P GYPSUM, 801 MINAKER DR., ANTIOCH, CA.  HE LEFT COLDWELL BANKER, 3711 LONE TREE WAY, ANTIOCH, CA AND DID NOT NOTICE ANY PROBLEMS WITH THE TOTES. UPON ARRIVING AT THE DOCK AT G-P GYPSUM IT WAS DISCOVERED THAT ONE OF THE TOTES HAD FAILED AND A SERIOUS LEAK HAD DEVELOPED.  EMERGENCY PRECAUTIONS WERE PUT INTO EFFECT BY G-P GYPSUM WHO CALLED 911.  THE TOTE SPILLED THE GREATER PART OF ITS CONTENTS AT THIS POINT AND THE G-P EMPLOYEES BUILT A BERM TO CONTINUE THE SPILL FROM ENTERING STORM DRAINS.  THE RESPONSE TEAMS DISCOVERED THAT A TRAIL FROM LONE TREE WAY WAS EVIDENT AND THAT THE FAILURE OCCURRED WHILE IN TRANSIT TO THE DESTINATION DELIVERY.  AFTER NOTIFYING WACKER CHEMICAL (517-263-3259) AND SPEAKING WITH SHARON ETCHERTHE PROPER MSDS SHEETS WERE FAXED AND THE CLEAN-UP COULD BE ORGANIZED.  THE COUNTY OF CONTRA COSTA AND THE CITY OF ANTIOCH PROCEEDED WITH THE CLEAN-UP OF THE CITY STREETS, USING A SOLUTION TO NEUTRALIZE THE RESIDUE SPILLED ALONG THE APPROXIMATELY 5 MILE ROUTE TO THE DELIVERY LOCATION.  G-P GYPSUM COORDINATED WITH CWX TO CLEAN-UP THE SITE WITH CONSOLIDATED WASTE MANAGEMENT.

column168: AT APPROXIMATELY 0715 HRS ON JUNE 17, 2005 A TRUCK DRIVER WAS UNLOADING SODIUM HYPOCHORITE SOLUTION (12.5%) FROM THE CARGO TANK MOTOR VEHICLE (ctmv) TO THE PLANT STORAGE TANK. T HE PLANT STORAGE TANK IS LOCATED INSIDE A CONCRETE CONTAINMENT DIKE.    WHILE UNLOADING, THE STORAGE TANK OVERFILLED AND APPROXIMATELY 2 GALLS OF THE SODIUM HYPOCHLORITE SOLUTION SPILLED FROM THE TANK OVERFLOW LINE AND INTO THE CONTAINMENT DIKE AREA.    DURING THE DUBSEQUENT INVESTIGATION, THE TRUCK DRIVER WAS INTERVIEWED VIA CONFERENCE CALL.  HE IDICATED THAT THE SIGHT GLASS ON THE STORAGE TANK WAS HAZY AND MADE THE TANK LEVEL DIFFICULT TO DISCERN.    THE DRIVER REPORTED THE INCIDENT TO THE OPERATOR WHO CLEANED THE DIKE ARE WITH WATER, INITIATED THE IVESTIGATION, COMPLETED AN INTERNA SPILL REPORT, AND REPORTED THE INCIDENT TO MANAGEMENT.    THERE WERE NO INJURIES OR PERSONNEL EXPOSURES.  THE TANK CAR DID NOT FAIL.  NO MATERIAL WAS RELEASED OUTSIDE THE CONTAINMENT AREA.
column169: THE CAUSE OF THE RELEASE WAS OVERFILLING THE STORAGE TANK.  THE TANK'S SIGHT GLASS HAD BECOME HAZY DUE TO WEATHERING AND THE LEVEL WAS DIFFICULT TO DISCERN, THUS THE OVERFILLING OCCURRED.  CORRECTIVE ACTIONS INCLUDED: 1) REPLACING THE TANK SIGHT GLASS, AND 2) CREATING A PREVENTATIVE MAINTENANCE PROCEDURE TO INSPECT THE GITH GLASS EVERY 6 MONTHS AND REPLACE AS NECESSARY.

GATX 18293, LOAD BUTYL ACRYLATE, WAS DISCOVERED TO BE LEAKING PRODUCT AT CSX TRANSPORTATION'S RAIL YARD IN MOBILE, AL.  THE CAR WAS REPORTED TO BE LEAKING CONTINUOUSLY FROM THE TOP WHILE IT WAS SITTING STILL.  IT WAS ISOLATED AND PLASTIC SHEETING WAS PLACED UNDER IT TO CONTAIN THE SPILLAGE.  THE SHIPPER, ARKEMA, INC, WAS NOTIFIED VIA CHEMTREC.  CSXT'S HAZARDOUS MATERIALS DEPARTMENT RESPONDED AN EMERGENCY RESPONSE CONTRACTOR TO THE YARD TO REPAIR THE LEAK.  THE CAR WAS FOUND TO BE LEAKING FROM THE PACKING RETAINER NUT ON THE OPERATING HANDLE FOR THE LQIUID EDUCTION LINE'S BALL VALVE.  THE CONTRACTOR RELIEVED THE PRESSURE ON THE CAR AND TIGHTENED THE PACKING NUT.  THE LEAK STOPPED.  THE CONTRACTOR REPORTED THAT THE PRODUCT EVAPORATED QUICKLY AND THERE WAS VERY LITTLE PRODUCT CONTAINED ON THE PLASTIC PLACED UNDER THE CAR.  THE MANWAY WAS OPENED TO CHECK THE PRODUCT LEVEL; THERE WAS ABOUT 6 INCHES OF OUTAGE.  ARKEMA WAS ADVISED OF THE CAUSE OF THE PRODUCT RELEASE.  THE CAR WAS RELEASED TO CONTINUE TO DESTINATION.  CAUSE CODE - 296  2(5+1+0) X (2+0) = 24

column58: Pressure Relief Valve or Device - Reclosing
column168: The leak was from the hydrostatic relief valve — relieving pressure build-up in the dispenser pump and piping system. The employee involved had started to make a delivery to the dispenser tank when the hydrostatic relief valve started to relieve pressure in the system. The employee shutdown the fill operation of the tank. At that time, he noticed an instantaneous water heater/power washer in operation nearby. The employee attempted to remove this possible source of ignition. Before he was able to do this, a flash fire resulted. This fire was fueled by the relief valve continuing intermittent release of gas. The employee was injured and was unable to perform any further shutdown action on the dispenser. The remaining gas in the dispenser continued to bum until the tank was empty.
column169: Make sure the dispensing pump is not running when the supply tank is being filled.

column168: (A) A BNSF TRAIN DERAILED FOUR HAZARDOUS MATERIAL LADENED TANK CARS IN A SIDING.  THE CAUSE WAS THE FIRST RAILCAR THAT DERAILED HAD STUFF TRUCK BOLSTERS AND FAILED TO NEGOTIATE THE SIDING SWITCH.  TWO OF THE FOUR DERAILED TANK CARS LEAKED PRODUCT.  UTLX 79998, BEHIND THE FIRST DERAILED RAILCAR, DERAILED ON ITS SIDE AND DRIPPED PRODUCT FROM ITS VACUUM RELIEF VALVE THAT FAILED TO HOLD BACK THE LIQUID PRESSURE ON THIS VALVE.  A RECEPTACLE WAS PLACED UNDER THE DRIP UNTIL UTLX 79998 WAS UPRIGHTED.  UTLX 79998'S DERAILMENT DAMAGE EXCEEDED ITS DEPRECIATED VALUE AND THE REMAINING PRODUCT IS PENDING TRANSFER TO EITHER ANOTHER SUITABLE TANK CAR OR TANKER TRUCKS.  (B) A BNSF TRAIN DERAILED FOUR HAZARDOUS MATERIALS LADENED TANK CARS ON SIDING TRACK.  AFTER INVESTIGATION, VICX 1772 (THE FIRST RAILCAR TO DERAIL) WAS REPORTED WITH NOTICEABLE WEAR AT THE CENTER PLATE AND BOWL, INDICATING A STIFF TRUCK BOLSTER AND ITS FAILURE TO NEGOTIATE THE SIDING SWITCH CAUSING THE DERAILMENT.  TWO OF THE FOUR TANK CARS LEAKED PRODUCT.  VICX 1772 DERAILED ON ITS SIDE AND DRIPPED PRODUCT FROM THE MANWAY CLOSURE CAUSED BY LOOSE MANWAY SECUREMENT BOLTS.  A RECEPTACLE WAS PLACED UNDER THE DRIP UNTIL VICX 1772 WAS UPRIGHTED.  VICX 1772'S DERAILMENT DAMAGE EXCEEDED ITS DEPRECIATED VALUE AND THE REMAINING PRODUCT INSIDE VICX 1772 IS PENDING FUTURE TRANSFER INTO EITHER ANOTHER SUITABLE TANK CAR OR TANKER TRUCKS.

column168: TRUCK ARRIVED AT IBM CORP., ESSEX JUNCTION, VERMONT, AND WAS BEING UNLOADED AT THE CHEMICAL DISTRIBUTION CENTER, WHEN A WET SPOT WAS DISCOVERED ON THE FLOOR OF THE TRUCK.  THERE WAS ONE DRUM FOUND ON THE TRUCK WITH LIQUID LEAKING OUT OF THE WEEP HOLE IN TOP OF THE DRUM.  THE DRUM WAS REMOVED FROM THE TRUCK AND CLEANED AND DURING THE PROCESS OF CLEANING, A CRACK ALONG THE RIM OF THE DRUM WAS DISCOVERED WITH THREE SMALL HOLES.  IT IS PRESUMED THAT THE MATERIAL IN THE DRUM CAME THROUGH THE TREE SMALL HOLES DURING TRANSIT, TRAVELED THROUGH THE WEEP HOLE, DOWN THE SIDE OF THE DRUM, AND ON TO THE FLOOR OF THE TRUCK.

ASSISTED BNSF RESPONDERS IN THE SUCCESSFUL INSTALLATION OF OF AN EMERGENCY KIT 'C' WHICH ENDED FURTHER PRODUCT VAPOR RELEASE INTO THE ATMOSPHERE PRIOR TO 1000 HRS. PDT. 6/26.  YARD OPERATIONS RESUMED AT THAT TIME ALSO.  SIX BNSF TRAINS WERE DELAYED THREE HOURS EACH.  ON 6/29/05, CONSIGNEE CONTRACT RESPONDERS DEPRESSURED GATX 56888 AND REPLACED THE FAULTY VAPOR VALVE.  THE VALVE SEAT OR FACE PLATE WAS FOUND TO BE GROOVED IN THE FAULTY VAPOR VALVE.  RESPONDERS CLEANED THE PRESSURE PLATE AREA, THE PROTECTIVE HOUSING INSIDE AND OUT; AND ALSO THE C-KIT.  GATX 56888 WAS MONITORED AND NO FURTHER RESIDUE PRODUCT VAPOR RELEASE WAS EVIDENT.

THE PREVIOUSLY APPLIED SRV WAS NOTED WITH THE TWO SPRING RETAINER NUTS (ADJUSTMENT & LOCK NUTS) MISSING, AS WELL AS, THE SPRING; ALL ASSUMED TO HAVE FALLEN INSIDE THE TANK.  ALL SPILLAGE EVAPORATED.

column168: Upon arrival to the destination facility the driver noted a small leak in the trailer.  During the unloading process it was discovered that a 5-gallon bucket was leaking through the lid.  The driver immediately phoned for a clean-up crew.      Upon arrival to the site, it was determined that approximately 1 gallon of Greasestrip Plus had been released onto the floor of the transport trailer.     The initial site evaluation revealed two areas of contamination. The first area was at the rear of the trailer and was approximately one foot by one foot in size. The second area was near the front of the trailer and was approximately two feet by two feet.     Clay absorbent was applied liberally to each area. The sorbent was then pushed across the contaminated area repeatedly with a stiff bristle broom. After the area had been worked for about half and hour, the sorbent material was pushed aside and fresh sorbent was added. After 15 minutes, that sorbent was also moved aside. A scraping bar was then used to scrape off any material that had dried and become stuck to the floor of the trailer. Any visible lumps or dark spots in the contaminated areas were scraped flat and the contaminant was removed. After scraping, the clay sorbent was swept over the areas again to pick up any remnants of the contaminant. The Clay sorbent was then swept up and placed in a 30 gallon open top poly drum. The drum was then sent off for disposal at a permitted solid waste management facility.  The entire on site cleanup took approximately 1 hour.
column169: It was unclear as to what caused this drum to leak.  We are recommending that all containers be checked for a proper seal at the shipper locations, then loaded for final destination.

TONIGHT IN ONTARIO CONTAINER AAZ25935 WAS UNLOADED IN THE ONT INTERNATIONAL IMPORT SORT.  DURING THE UNLOADING OF THIS CONTAINER WE DISCOVERED EVIDENCE THAT A FIRE HAD TAKEN PLACE INSIDE THE CONTAINER.  A LARGE HEAVY GAUGE PLASTIC BAG CONTAINING NUMEROUS SMALL PACKAGES AND DOCUMENTS WAS FOUND INSIDE THE CONTAINER.  THE PLASTIC BAG HAD A LARGE MELTED HOLE WITH BURN MARKS AROUND THE EDGES OF THE HOLE.  WE OPENED THE BAG AND DISCOVERED NUMEROUS DAMAGED PACKAGES.  THE PACKAGE IDENTIFIED AS THE SOURCE PACKAGE CONTAINED BATTERY PACKS.  BASED ON INFORMATION OBTAINED FROM THE LOADING HANDLING SYSTEM, THIS CONTAINER WAS GENERATED IN PVG (SHANGHAI, CHINA), IT ARRIVED INTO ONT ON UPS 7929/29JUN05.  AT THE TIME OF THE CONTAINER UNLOAD IN ONT, THE PLASTIC BAG AND ITS CONTENTS WERE COOL TO THE TOUCH AND THERE WAS NO SMOLDERING OF ANY OF THE CONTENTS.  UPON UNLOAD DISCOVERY, THE SOURCE PACKAGE WAS ISOLATED FOR FAA INSPECTION.
column169: FAA HAS BEEN NOTIFIED.  AGENT WENDELL WOODSON VISITED THE ONTARIO FACILITY AND TOOK PICTURES OF THE PACKAGE FOR HIS INVESTIGATION.

THE BOTTLES WERE FINALLY NEUTRALIZED, CESQG PROCEDURES FOLLOWED & DISPOSED OF IN THE TRASH.  ONE BOTTLE MUST HAVE BEEN MISSED IN THE UNLOAD AND HAD A MISSING CAP THE FOLLOWING DAY (6/24/05)  A PART-TIME SUPERVISOR IN THE SORT AREA KNOCKED THE BOTTLE OFF THE SORT SLIDE AND SOME OF THE PRODUCT SPILLED ON HIS LOWER RIGHT LEG CAUSING IRRITATION. THE EMPLOYEE SUGHT MEDICAL ATTENTION AND WAS RELEASED WITH OINT/NO RESTRIC

column168: TRACTOR-TRAILER UNIT PULLED INTO TERMINAL FOR A WHILE.  DRIVER WAS MAKING PRE-TRIP INSPECTION PRIOR TO DEPARTING THE TERMINAL AND OBSERVED A LIQUID MATERIAL LEAKING FROM THE TRAILER UNIT.  SOME OF THE LIQUID HAD IMPACTED THE GRAVEL PARKING LOT AREA.  ENTRY WAS MADE INTO THE TRAILER.  IT WAS OBSERVED THAT THERE WERE TWENTY 5-GALLON CONTAINERS OF PAINT PRODUCT AND ONE HUNDRED THIRTY (130) 30-GALLON CONTAINERS.  IT WAS OBSERVED THAT THE 30-GALLON CONTAINERS WERE ON PALLETS BUT WERE NOT BANDED OR WAS THERE ANY TYPE OF BARRIER (SUCH AS CARDBOARD) BETWEEN THE 30-GALLON METAL DRUMS.  WHILE IN TRANSPORTATION MODE, THE DRUMS RUBBED AGAINST EACH OTHER CAUSING DAMAGE TO THE CONTAINER.  SEVEN OF THE DRUMS WERE DISCOVERED TO BE LEAKING AT THE MID LEVEL OF THE DRUM AT THE CHIME.  APPROXIMATELY 20 GALLONS OF PRODUCT WAS RELEASED.  ANOTHER 54 DRUMS SHOWED EXCESSIVE WEAR AROUND THE CHIME AND WERE NOT IN SHIPPABLE CONDITION.  A TOTAL OF SIXTY ONE (61) 30-GALLON DRUMS WERE PLACED INTO 55-GALLON OPEN TOP METAL DRUMS.  THE OUTER DRUM WAS THEN LABELED WITH THE REQUIRED INFORMATION SUCH AS PROPER SHIPPING NAME, HAZARD CLASS, UN NUMBER, PACKING GROUP, AND APPROPRIATE HAZARD CLASS LABELS.  THE TRAILER FLOOR WAS CLEANED ALONG WITH CONTAMINATED GRAVEL.

WHILE MAKING A DELIVERY OF DIESEL FUEL AT WILKINSON BUS GARAGE IN CRESSON, PA A COUPLING DEVICE CAME UNHOOKED AND RELEASED 50 GALLONS OF PRODUCT INTO THEIR PARKING LOT.  THE UNDERGROUND TANK'S OVER FILL PROTECTION DEVICE ACTIVATED, AND THE DIESEL BACKED UP THE FILL TUBE INTO OUR CO-AXIAL ELBOW.  THIS BACK PRESSURE CAUSED A COVER CAP TO BLOW OFF THE ELBOW, AND THE DIESEL THEN SPILLED ONTO THE PARKING LOT.  IT FLOWED FOR SEVERAL SECONDS UNTIL THE DRIVER SHUT OFF THE DRY LOCK VALVE ON THE TRAILER.  OUR DRIVER TIMOTHY AURANDT PA 22-711-621) LIMITED THE RELEASE TO THE BLACK TOP PARKING LOT, COLLECTED ALL THE STANDING PRODUCT WITH OUR SPILL MATERIALS, AND THEN NOTIFIED OUR OFFICE.  THEN WE IMMEDIATELY SENT A CREW TO FINISH THE REMEDIATION.
column172: Tank truck, tank mounted on truck chassis

column168: THE VALVE ON A 150LB AMMONIA WAS STUCK SLIGHTLY OPEN.  THE AIRGAS EMERGENCY RESPONSE TEAM INVESTIGATED AND ATTEMPTED TO CLOSE THE VALVE.  THIS WAS UNSUCCESSFUL AND AN EMERGENCY "A" KIT WAS APPLIED.  AFTER BEING GRANTED AN EMERGENCY EXEMPTION TO TRANSPORT THE CYLINDER IT WAS RETURNED TO THE VENDOR FOR REMEDIATION.

column168: DRIVER WAS DELIVERING TO A 1,000 GALLON GENERATOR TANK, WHEN HE UNHOOKED NOZZLE, THE TANK WAS OVERFILED, AND APPROXIMATED 5 TO 10 GALLONS OF OIL RAN OUT OF THE FILL, ON TO A CONCRETE PAD.  IT WAS CLEANED UP W/SPILL PADS & STAY DRY IMMEDIATELY.  MDE NOTIFIED @ 1124.
column169: DRIVER WAS TRAINED ON PROPER PROCEDURE FOR FILLING GENERATOR TANK.

column168: OUR DRIVER WAS OFFLOADING ONE COMPARTMENT OF THE TRAILER INTO THE CUSTOMERS UST WHEN APPROXIMATELY 100 GALLONS OF FUEL WAS RELEASED FROM AN OLD UNCAPPED 2" FILL ON THE UST.  CUSTOMER CONTACTED THEIR CLEAN-UP CONTRACTOR TO HANDLE REMEDIATION.  KENTUCKY EPA ON THE SCENE AND CONFIRMED THAT THIS SPILL WAS A RESULT OF PROBLEMS WITH OUR CUSTOMERS UST AND NOT OUR DRIVERS UNLOADING PROCEDURES.
column169: CONTINUING EDUCATION INTO PROPER UNLOADING PROCEDURES.

column168: OUR DRIVER NOTICED A LEAK COMING FROM THE FRONT OF THE TRAILER DURING A DOT SAFETY INSPECTION.  RESPONDERS PUT OUT ABSORBENT MATERIAL TO PREVENT THE MATERIAL FROM ENTERING A STORM DRAIN.  UNIVAR USA ENTERED THE TRAILER, PLACED THE DRUM INTO AN OVERPACK DRUM.  A SMALL NAIL HOLE WAS SEEN IN THE BOTTOM OF THE DRUM AND A NAIL HEAD WAS HAMMERED BACK INTO THE PALLET.  THE MATERIAL ON THE TRAILER AND ON THE GROUND WAS NEUTRALIZED, PICKED UP AND DISPOSED OF.  THE SURROUNDING AREA WAS THEN WASHED DOWN WITH 1500 GALS OF WATER AND CHECKED FOR PH TO CLEAN.
column169: PALLET SUPPLIER WAS CONTACTED TO VERIFY WEIGHT CAPACITY OF PALLET PURCHASED.  WAREHOUSE INSTRUCTED TO INSPECT PALLETS BEFORE PUTTING A LOAD ON THEM.

column168: A EMPLOYEE OF MORRIS COOP FILED A 1000 GALLON NH3 NURSE TANK TO 85% AT 15:30, & PARKED IT AT THE FENCED IN MORRIS COOP BULK PLANT.  AT 6:00 A 911 CALLER REPORTED AN ANHYDROUS EXPLOSION AT THE MORRIS COOP BULK PLANT.  THE NURSE TANK BLEW APPROXIMATELY A 31" X 29 1/2" HOLE IN THE LEFT REAR OF THE TANK.  A VAPOR CLOUD OF NH3 FORMED & MOVED WESTWARD WITH THE WIND 3-5 MPH.  THE DISIPATED ON VERY SHORT TIME NO CLEANUP WAS NEEDED

AFTER SHIPPER LOADED THE TANKER, THE DRIVER PERFORMED A PRE-TRIP INSPECTION ON THE TANKER.  THE DRIVER FOUND 3 DOME LIDS CLOSED BUT UNSECURED, AND SECURED THE DOME LIDS IMMEDIATELY.  THE 4TH DOME LID WAS CLOSED BUT NOT SECURED BY THE DRIVER.  THE DRIVER THOUGHT THE TANKER HAD ONLY 3 DOME LIDS AND THE 4TH BOX CONTAINED THE VACUUM LINES.  WHEN THE DRIVER STOPPED FOR A RED LIGHT, THE LOAD MOVED FOWARDS AND BACKWARDS, AND SPLASHED OUT OF THE UNSECURED DOME LID.  THE DRIVER NOTICED MATERIAL SPILLING FROM THE TANKER, STOPPED TRAFFIC, AND DIRECTED TRAFFIC AWAY FROM THE SPILL.  A SPILL RESPONSE COMPANY WAS CONTACTED AND ARRIVED ON-S9TE WITHIN 30 MINUTES.
column169: FOLLOW-UP TRAINING WITH DRIVER.

column168: RECEIVED RAILCAR RBOX20139 WITH 32 SUPERSACKS OF COPPER SULFATE, PLUS PALLETIZED 50 LBS. BAGS OF SAME. 8 OF THE SUPERSACKS HAD DAMAGE TO THEM AND HAD LOST SIGNIFICANT PRODUCT INSIDE THE BOXCAR. LOAD WAS NOT PROPERLY SECURED AND INADEQUATE (SCRAP) PALLETS WERE USED UNDER MOST BAGS.  COPPER SULFATE INSIDE BOXCAR WAS SHOVELED UP AND PUT IN 6X55 GALLON OPEN HEAD DRUMS AND LABELED A SPRODUCT FOR DISCOUNT SALE. PRODUCT THAT FELL BETWEEN THE CRACKS ON THE BOXCAR TO THE GROUND AND PRODUCT CONTAMINATED BY DIRT/DEBRIS INSIDE RAILCAR WAS PUT IN 55 GALLON OPEN HEAD DRUMS AND LABELED AS HAZARDOUS WASTE (2 1/2 DRUMS). A FINAL VACUUM OF THE GROUND INSIDE OF RAILCAR, AND RAILCAR UNDER STRUCTURE WAS DONE BEFORE RAILCAR WAS ALLOWED TO MOVE.   THE ONLY SHORING OF LOAD WAS RIGHT IN FRONT OF THE DOORS. PRODUCT ON ENDS OF RAILCAR WAS NOT SHORED. ADDITIONALY, PALLETS WERE STACKED THREE HIGH IN BOTH ENDS OF THE BOXCAR WITH PALLET RIGHTS OF ONLY TWO TOWARDS THE MIDDLE. THERE WAS NO BRACING TO KEEP 3 HIGH PALLETS FROM FALLING DOWN ONTO 2 HIGH PALLETS.  ESTIMATED 1400 POUNDS COPPER SULFATE PENTA HYDRATE LOST BETWEEN LAREDO, TX AND SPOKANE, WA.
column169: FURTHER LOADS OF PALLETIZED LOADS OF ANY PRODUCT NEED TO REQUIRE (ON PO TO VENDRO) THAT PRODUCT IS PLACED ON PALLETS RATED TO HANDLE A MINIMUM OF 3000 LBS.; THAT THE PRODUCT IS CONTAINED WITHIN THE DIMENSIONS OF THE PALLET; THAT PALLETS ARE PROTECTED FROM RUBBING AGAINST EACH OTHER AND THE SIDE OF THE RAILCAR OR TRAILER; AND THAT PROPER BRACING IS USED TO PREVENT LOAD FROM SHIFTING.

column168: Driver attempted to deliver 6200 gallons into 9403 gallon capacity manifolded tanks. The stick readings showed room for 8062 gallons. Unbeknownst to the driver, pressure variations in the tank caused by the vapor recovery system caused the stick readings to be incorrect. He overfilled the tank, when removing the hose fitting product "burpped" out the fill tube and was released onto the driveway.  Flow as for 20/30 seconds, 25 gallons. Driver notified customer at fills to have employees shut down pumps and call the Fire Dept. Driver used spill pads to stop the flow into the street and drain and grabbed up some mulch bags to build a dyke around the drain.
column169: Training in July and December 2005 was provided for all drivers, terminal personnell and dispatchers about this incident for improved operating procedures. When a overfill condition or high tank alarm exists drivers must wait 10-15 minutes for tank pressure to equalize prior to disconnecting the hose.  If driver encounters any problems during delivery, the delivery must be aborted. Veeder root inventory reports must be verified for "time/date" stamp to confirm it is current. Dispatch is check veeder root before setting up the load; and will send out loads that fit in the tanks by compartment only.

column168: A PRESSURE SAFETY VALVE (PSV) ON AN AMMONIA TRAILER OPERATED BY BUTTON TRANSPORTATION OPENED AND RELEASED AMMONIA TO THE ATMOSHPERE. THE TRUCK/TRAILER WAS LOADING AT RACK 3 AT THE AGRIUM, WEST SACRAMENTO FACILITY AT THE TIME OF THE INCIDENT. STATEMENTS FROM VARIOUS PLANT PERSONNEL WERE TAKEN (EH&S SUPERVISOR). THERE WERE AT THE TIME OF THE INCIDENT TWO AMMONIA LOADING CONTROL SYSTEMS, THE OLDER USING BROOKS METERS AND AT THE TIME, ONLY ON RACKS 3 & 4, AND THE NEWER DIGITAL CONTROL SYSTEM (DCS) CONTROLLING RACKS 1 & 2. THE BROOKS METERES REQUIRE THE INPUT OF THE TARGET NET WEIGHT OF AMMONIA AND THE DCE REQUIRES TARGET GROSS WEIGHT. THE OPERATOR WAS BUSY WITH SEVERAL TRUCKS AT THE TIME AND ERRONEOUSLY KEYED IN A GROSS WEIGHT TO AN INSTRUMENT THAT REQUIRED A NET WEIGHT APPROXIMATELY 40,000 LBS LESS. THE SYSTEM ATTEMPTED TO DELIVER AN EXCESS AMOUNT OF AMMONIA TO THE TRUCK. AS THE TANK FILLED BEYOND ITS INTENDED CAPACITY, THE PRESSURE ROSE RAPIDLY IN THE REDUCED HEAD SPACE SLOWING THE FILL-RATE AND THE PSV OPENED. SHIFT PERSONNEL RESPONDED TO THE RELEASE BY STOPPING THE LOADING AND MOVING PERSONS IN THE AREA. ADMINISTRATION PERSONNEL WERE MADE AWARE OF THE RELEASE AND SUBSEQUENTLY ALSO RESPONDED.    REGULATORY AND NEIGHBOR NOTIFICATIONS WERE MADE BY PLANT PERSONNEL. NO INJURIES OR PROPERTY DAMAGE OCCURED.    IT WAS SUBSEQUENTLY CALCULATED BY ENGINEERING SUPPORT PERSONNEL THAT APPROXIMATELY 48 LBS OF AMMONIA IN VAPOR FORM WERE RELEASED TO THE ATMOSPHERE. A REVIEW OF DIGITAL RECORDINGS OF THE SECURITY CAMERAS SHOWED THE INCIDENT FROM THE CAMERA ON THE AREA WAREHOUSE AND THAT THE CLOUD DID NOT VISIBLY MIGRATE OFF SITE.    Causes  1. Incorrect load number input.  2. Two systems operable at the same time.  3. Failure to check/monitor/correct input error or monitor loading process.  4. Failure to communicate/coordinate — did not ask for help as task load increased.
column169: 1. PROVIDE TRAINING TO COVER:     I.  AT THE TRUCK RACKS, IF THERE IS A PROBLEM, INITIATE THE STOP THEN EVALUATE THE PROBLEM. "STOP THEN THINK".    II. FOR SCALE-HOUSE PERSONNEL; EMPHASIZING THE NEED TO BE IN THE SCALE HOUSE WHEN AMMONIA LOADING IS TAKING PLACE AND NOT TO ATTEMPT TO DEAL WITH TOO MANY TRUCKS SIMUTANEOUSLY.

column168: There were 4ea 5 Gal pails of Hydrochloric acid (HCL) were placed on in a K-max box for shipment to Port Fourchon LA.  The Box was then loaded and secured onto the transportation truck.  At the time the K-max box was loaded the drain plugs were not installed.  The truck then started movement to the final destination.  The truck was on the road for about 100 Miles when the drive saw something smoking on the back of his truck. The Driver called in the spill and a Halliburton HSE Coordinator responded.  Halliburton Called a third party clean up crew to mitigate the spill and clean up the area.  Further investigation showed there was a hair line crack on the side of one of the HCL containers.  The containers were stored outside and were stating to deteriorate due to the exposure to the elements.  Approximately 2.5 GAL of HCL leaked in the K-max box and some did spill onto the bed of the transport truck.
column169: The five gal totes are now stored inside to prevent the damage to the container due to exposure to the elements.       We have also reviewed our process and have made improvements to include better inspections of our load before we put it on the truck.

column168: ON JUNE 2, 2005, A TRACTOR-TRAILER OPERATED BY KLLM TRANSPORT SERVICES WAS TRAVELING WESTBOUND ON I-80 WHEN A NEARBY VEHICLE BROUGHT THE DRIVERS ATTENTION TO A LEAK COMING OUT OF THE REAR OF THE TRAILER.  THE TRACTOR-TRAILER EXITED THE INTERSTATE AND THE DRIVER OBSERVED A LIQUID SUBSTANCE COMING OUT OF THE REAR AND FRONT OF THE TRAILER.  THE BILL OF LADING INDICATED THAT SEVERAL CORROSIVE ITEMS WERE ON BOARD.  ON JUNE 2, 2005, CURA EMERGENCY SERVICES (CES) WAS CONTACTED BY KLLM TRANSPORT SERVICES TO MANAGE THE CLEAN UP OPERATIONS FOLLOWING THIS INCIDENT.  CES CONTACTED THE DRIVER OF THE VEHICLE TO GAIN SUPPORTING INFORMATION ON THIS RELEASE.  THE DRIVER INFORMED CES AS TO WHAT WAS ON BOARD THE TRAILER AND MADE CES AWARE THAT HE NOTICED A LEAK COMING FROM THE FRONT AND REAR OF THE TRAILER.  THE MATERIAL WAS OBSERVED POOLING UP UNDER NEATH THE TRAILER ON THE ROAD SHOULDER.  BASED ON THE INFORMATION GIVEN, CES DISPATCHED A CREW FROM WEAVERTOWN ENVIRONMENTAL TO PERFORM A SITE ASSESSMENT AND NECESSARY CORRECTIVE ACTIONS ON SITE.  ON JUNE 2, 2005, A CREW FROM THE WEAVERTOWN ENVIRONMENTAL MOBILIZED TO THE SITE AND OBSERVED A SLOW LEAK COMING FROM THE FRONT AND REAR OF THE TRAILER.  THE CREW SOLIDIFIED THE RELEASE UNDERNEATH THE TRAILER WITH ABSORBENTS AND HAND EXCAVATED THE SPENT ABSORBENTS.  WEAVERTOWN TECHNICIANS DONNED LEVEL () PPE AND ENTERED THE TRAILER TO LOCATE THE SOURCE OF THE RELEASE.  ONCE INSIDE, THE CREW FOUND TWO 55-GALLON DRUMS OF ADVANTAGE PLUS AND ONE 55-GALLON DRUM OF SULFURIC ACID LEAKING.  IT APPEARED THAT THE DRUMS SUFFERED DAMAGE AS A RESULT OF A LOAD SHIFT.  ONCE THE RELEASE WAS CONTAINED THE TRACTOR-TRAILER WAS MOVED OFF OF THE RAMP AND THE CREW OFF-LOADED THE TRAILER FOR DECONTAMINATION.  THE CREW SPREAD FLOOR DRY INSIDE THE TRAILER AND WORKED THEM IN.  THE SPENT ABSORBENTS WERE COLLECTED INTO DRUMS FOR DISPOSAL.  THE DAMAGED DRUMS WERE OVERPACKED AND PLACED BACK ON THE TRAILER.  ALL OTHER CONTAINERS AND PALLETS WERE PLACED BACK ON THE TRAILER BEFORE THE TRUCK LEFT THE SITE.

column168: While pressurizing railcar SHPX 207221 loaded with Sulfuric Acid, our loader opened the product valves on the double valve assembly.  As he opened the second valve, he heard product coming up the induction pipe and then a light pop sound.  At that moment, product started spraying out between the flange that we attach our fitting too and the flange for the induction tube.  The duration of the release lasted for approximately 30 minutes.    The loader descended the railcar and got away from spray that was being released.  Another loader located on an acid rack two cars away noticed the incident and immediately went to the air line pressurizing the railcar and disconnected the air hose at the source. This allowed the railcar to start releasing pressure.
column169: All SHPX Series 207 railcar are not to be unloaded until such time that RESCAR changes out the incorrect flange gasket with the correct flange gasket.

According to the information obtained the following occurred.  Upon opening the trailer doors, four leaking twenty liter plastic pails were discovered tipped over in the trailer.  Approximately ten ounces of free product were released.  Inland Waters Pollution Control, Inc. of Cleveland, OH was dispatched to perform the cleanup.  Inland Waters Pollution Control, Inc. performed the cleanup using Level B protection and absorbent pads.  The cleanup materials, four leaking pails and remaining twenty-two pails were placed into overpack drums and returned to the shipper.  One BAX Global/The Brink's Company employee was exposed to the release.  The Material Safety Data Sheet was requested and received.
column169: Since the release was considered to be accidental, no actions have been taken to prevent future incidents.

column168: The shipment was booked with one item of hazardous material (Isopropanol Solution, Class 3, UN 1219, Limited Quantity) for loading on the Hapag-Lloyd Container Line vessel Antwerpen Express from Savannah, Georgia to Singapore.      The shipper advised Hapag-Lloyd after the vessel had sailed from Savannah of additional hazardous material (Aerosols, Class 2, UN 1950, Limited Quantity) in the container that was not originally booked or otherwise identified.    The shipping papers that accompanied the freight container to the marine terminal did not indicate the presence of the additional hazardous material, and the container was not placarded and/or marked to reflect the presence of the additional item.    The shipper subsequently provided corrected hazardous material shipping papers to Hapag-Lloyd.

column168: Driver picked up load in Mesquite, TX and visually verified openings of the IBCs were secured.  He stopped after approximately 40 miles in Waxahachie, TX to check the load.  Everything was fine.  He drove approximately 120 miles and stopped for fuel.  Once again he visually verified there were no leaks and openings were secured.  Driver noted that the exit from the fuel center had many potholes.    Approximately 20 miles further, driver was stopped for an inspection.  Officer noted material leaking.  Driver checked IBCs and found one had no cap.  Cap was laying on top of the container.  The top portion of the cap had come off leaving the threaded portion in the container.    Driver estimates the faulty cap was dislodged when leaving the fuel center.
column169: Univar was contacted immediately and informed of the situation.  They dispatched personnel with a new cap and materials for clean up.  (Note: this was the first use for the container.)    Dallas & Mavis terminal manager held team meeting to enforce the importance of checking the integrity of package closures.

column168: Driver checked in at plant with cargo tank.  Told unloader what he was delivering and gave him paperwork.  Plant employee showed him where to hook up. column169: The plant needs to label the fill lines with trade name and number so driver can verify with the BOL.

column168: At approximately 12:30 PM a NCRA driver took the wrong turn and ended up on a private asphalt road adjacent to the Conoco/Phillips refinery near Borger, Texas. When attempting to turn around, the driver backed into a parking/driveway area to a maintenance building where he backed into a hoist. The arm on the hoist punctured the back upper right side of the cargo tank creating a 3 inch long slit and dented the cargo tank (16 inches in diameter by 1.5 inches deep) Approximately 1.5 barrels of crude oil leaked onto the private road and driveway. The Conoco/Phillips refinery employees responded to the incident, immediately unloaded 70 barrels of the crude oil into a vacuum truck and cleaned up the spill. A NCRA truck was dispatched to the location to completely unload the damaged truck and the vacuum truck. The media cleaned up was disposed at a non-haz landfarm at the Conoco/Phillips refinery. The total incident took approximately 3 hours.
column169: The post incident review indicated that the driver was nervous when he realized he was on a private drive adjacent to the refinery. He was reprimanded for improper backing and not following defensive driving skills.

column168: FILE 05-173-D/SHIPPER: EMS AWB# CLU 37962569444 BMG  ON 6-20-2005 AT 1545 THE HAZ-MAT HOTLINE RECEIVED A CALL FROM THE BLOOMINGTON STATION LOCATED AT 2200 N CURRY PIKE, BLOOMINGTON, IN 47404.  FIELD SERVICE SUPERVISOR CHRIS SCHAPKER REPORTED HE HAD A LEAKING SHIPMENT.  THE HOTLINE CONTACTED THE HMHTTC SPILL RESPONSE TEAM.  UPON ARRIVAL THEY FOUND A FIBERBOARD BOX THAT CONTAINED A ONE GALLON BOTTLE OF ACETONE.  THE BOTTLE LEAKED THE ENTIRE ONE GALLON DUE TO BEING BROKEN IN TWO.  THE PACKAGE ARRIVED TO THE BLOOMINGTON STATION ON TRUCK #7087.  THIS SHIPMENT WAS PROPERLY MARKED AND LABELED ALONG WITH THE PROPER SHIPPERS DECLARATION FOR DANGEROUS GOODS ATTACHED.  CLEAR OF SCENE: 1906

THE TRL ORIGINALLY HAD A LEAK.  WE HAD TAKEN THE TRAILER TO SIOUXLAND TRAILER SALES, IN SIOUX CITY, IA FOR REPAIR. SIOUXLAND TRAILER SALES IS A CERTIFIED TANK REPAIR SERVICE FACILITY WHO CAN WORK ON CODED TRAILER.  THEY HAD WELDED ON THE TANK AND HYDROTESTED IT WHEN THEY WERE FINISHED.  SUPPOSELY EVERYTHING CHECKED OUT OK, SO WE TOOK THE TRAILER AND PUT IT BACK INTO SERVICE.  THE TRL WAS TAKEN TO MARINETTE, WI AND WAS LOADED FOR BLAIR, NE.  CPT PICKED UP THE TRL AND LEFT 8 AM FOR BLAIR, NE.  THE DRIVER HAD STOPPED AROUND 10:30AM AT A REST AREA.  HE DID A WALK-AROUND INSPECTION AND EVERYTHING WAS OK.  WHILE THE DRIVER WAS PROCEDING AROUND MADISON, WI AT 12PM.  HE WAS NOTIFIED BY ANOTHER TRUCK, WHO WAS FOLLOWING, THAT OUR TRL WAS LEAKING.  OUR DRIVER IMMEDIATELY PULLED OVER TO THE SHOULDER.  WHEN HE PULLED OVER WITH HIS HAZARD LIGHTS ON, A LAW OFFICER STOPPED BEHIND HIM TO SEE WHAT THE PROBLEM WE HAD.  WHEN THE LAW OFFICER AND OUR DRIVER DISCOVERED THE TRL LEAKING, THEY NOTIFIED THE EMERGENCY RESPONSE PEOPLE AND CENTRAL PETROLEUM.  WE AT C.P.T. TOLD THE DRIVER TO HAVE THE AUTHORITIES TO GET A BABY WADING POOL & FLOOR DRY TO HELP CONTAIN THE LEAKING PROD TILL SOMEONE COULD GET THERE TO UNLOAD TRL.  WE ALSO NOTIFIED CHEMTREC AS WELL AS NATURE WORKS, ABOUT THE INCIDENT.  WE ALSO STARTED CALLING TRUCK COMPANIES & TRL SALES CO. TO FIND SOMEONE WHO COULD UNLOAD US & STORE PROD OR WOULD ABLE TO DELIVER THE LOAD TO BLAIR, NE.  AFTER MANY CALLS WE WERE UNABLE TO FIND ANY ONE ABLE TO HELP US WITH THIS TASK.  THE EMERGENCY AUTHORITIES CALLED IN A DISPOSAL COMPANY IN AND HAD THE TRL PUMPED OFF.  THEN THEY SENT THE PRODUCT TO THE LOCAL SEWAGE TREATMENT PLANT FOR DISPOSAL

column168: Driver stated he was off loading into a vertical above ground tank that has an associated 3 and 4 inch steel piping with no shut off valve, only a pipe cap fitting. While pumping he observed the product in the tank was encroaching where the piping entered the tank near the top. Driver shut down so product would not begin to exit through the piping back to his trailer. He notified plant personal and an employee brought a 55-gallon drum and placed it under the tank piping and trailer hose connection. The plant employee quickly removed the hose fitting which caused a sudden release of 8 to 10 gallons of product onto the surrounding ground. Consignee employee's cleaned up and disposed of spill.

column168: ON 6/2/05 OUR EMPLOYEE INADVERTENTELY HOOKED UP A HOSE TO THE WRONG STEM VALVE.  THE LINE VALVE HAD NOT BEEN CLOSED EARLIER THAT DAY.  PRODUCT RAN THROUGH THE HOSE AND THE HOSE POPPED OVER TANK CONTAINMENT SPILLING ON ASPHALT AND TOWARD THE NW CORNER OF OUR SITE.  WHEN THE SPILL WAS NOTICED, PERSONNEL IMMEDIATELY SHUT OFF THE PUMP, CONTAINED THE SPILL BY DIKING THE SUMP, USING SPILL PADS TO ABSORB PRODUCT ON THE GROUND AND CALLED IN A CONTRACTOR TO PUMP OUT THE OIL/WATER SEPERATOR.
column169: THE LINES AND PUMPS VALVES WERE RELABELED.  THE LINE NOW HAS A LOCKING CAP.  OPERATING PROCEDURES WERE AMENDED TO ADD REMOVING THE HOSE FROM THE LINE AFTER USE.  ALL EMPLOYEES WERE TRAINED IN THESE NEW PROCEDURES AND RETRAINED IN LOADING AND UNLOADING PROCEDURES.

We were notified by the shipper that he had "a couple of cans of varnish" in the container he was shipping that were not previously declared. I proceeded to notify the local USCG COTP office to inform them of this discovery. The container was placed on hold by the USCG until the shipper cound provide us with the revised supporting documentation. After we received the documents from the shipper, I notified the USCG and they came out to the terminal to review them. The shipment was then released by the USCG. The shipper stated that he is not in the business of shipping but, only ships the container (with his boating supplies) for international boating events. It appears to be an honest mistake by his part.

THE WABASH ALLOYS DRIVER LEFT FOR TOLEDO, OH AFTER PERFORMING HIS NORMAL PRE-TRIP INSPECTION OF THE TRAILER, TRACTOR, AND CRUCIBLE.  SHORTLY AFTER HE HAD DEPARTED ON OLD 24 HE NOTICED A LEAK IN THE TAP SIDE OF THE CRUCIBLE.  THE DRIVER THEN PULLED OFF INTO THE GRASS AND NOTIFIED THE SCALE HOUSE AT THE PLANT.  PLANT EMPLOYEES WERE THEN DISPATCHED WITH WOOL AND WATER TO THE SCENE OF THE LEAK TO CONTAIN IT.  THE WOOL WAS APPLIED AROUND THE PLUG AND WATER APPLIED UNTIL THE LEAK WAS STOPPED APPROXIMATELY 15 MINUTES LATER.  THE CRUCIBLE WAS THEN RETURNED TO THE PLANT AND INSPECTED.  IT WAS DETERMINED THE TAP HOLE CONE HAD BEEN DRIVEN IN TOO FAR.  THE CRUCIBLE WAS THEN PLUGGED AND INSPECTED SEVERAL TIMES BEFORE IT WAS DETERMINED THE PROBLEM WAS FIXED.  THE CRUCIBLE WAS THEN DELIVERED TO TOLEDO WITHOUT INCIDENT.  EMPLOYEES FROM THE PLANT CLEANED UP THE SPILL TOTALING 42LBS OF METAL ON THE ROAD AND 300LBS. FROM THE GROUND.  THE METAL WAS RETURNED TO THE PLANT TO BE MELTED.  NO SIGNIFICANT DAMAGE OCCURRED TO ANY PROPERTY OR PERSON.  POLICE AND EMERGENCY RESPONSE PERSONNEL WERE AT THE SCENE.
column169: EMPLOYEES DIRECTLY RESPONSIBLE FOR INSTALLING TAP HOLE CONES WILL BE REFRESHED AND REINSTRUCTED ON PROPER PROCEDURES FOR INSTALLATION TO MINIMIZE FUTURE INCIDENTS.  WABASH ALLOYS ALSO IS REVIEWING OUR EMERGENCY RESPONSE PROCEDURES AND MAKING CHANGES THAT ARE DEEMED NECESSARY TO INSURE FUTURE INCIDENTS ARE REPORTED PROPERLY.

column17: Reporter: ELI LILLY & COMPANY, TIPPECANOE LABORATORIES
column168: A Sulfuric Acid tank truck arrived at Eli Lily and Company, Tippecanoe Labs and was staged at the T117 sampling rack.  The lading was received and a sample was obtained through the man-way dome by an Eli Lilly employee.  The man-way closure gasket fell out of its seat during sampling and was replaced in the gasket seat before closing the man-way by the Eli Lilly sampling operator.  All dome wing nuts were hand tightened with one being tightened further with the use of a tool.  Tanker was then relocated to the holding area just west of the sampling rack by the carrier (Frick Trucking) until Eli Lilly Quality Control approval was obtained.  After Eli Lilly Quality Control approval, the cargo tank was enroute via Frick Trucking to the appropriate unloading station when an Eli Lilly employee noticed that the tanker was leaking as it was stopped at a STOP sign.  The truck had traveled 400 feet from the Quality Control Approval staging truck pad to the STOP sign where the leak was discovered.  The truck was held at this point by the Eli Lilly employee and Eli Lilly security was contacted.  The on-site Eli Lilly Emergency Response Team responded to the spill and spread Sodium Carbonate to to neutralize the acid.  The Sodium Carbonate was collected and drummed for disposal.  An investigation was conducted and the primary cause of the leak was determined as the man-way gasket becoming dislodged from it's seat preventing a tight seal.  As the truck started and stopped, the Sulfuric Acid spilled out from under the man-way closure.   The closure gasket alignment was corrected and the man-way closure was tightened down securely by the Eli Lilly Emergency Response Team.  The truck was then moved to the unloading station by the Frick Trucking driver to be unloaded by DOT trained Eli Lilly operators according to Eli Lilly procedure.     Carrier information:  Frick Trucking LLC  P.O. Box 40  Wawaka, Indiana  46794    Federal ID Number    1035827    Hazmat Registration Number   062105551 040N
column169: Eli Lilly and Company, Tippecanoe Labs, Lafayette, IN has reinforced DOT training and sampling procedures with the sampling operators. Procedures will be reviewed and revised if needed to include verbiage explaining that closure gaskets are to be correctly seated and all screw type closure devices are to be tool tightened.

column17: Reporter: Eli Lilly & Company, Tippecanoe Laboratories
column168: Eli Lilly and Company owned cargo tanker # TT321R67 was loaded with RCRA hazardous liquid waste by Eli Lilly and Company, Tippecanoe Laboratories, Lafayette, IN on the evening of 06-23-2005. The tanker was then relocated to an on site tanker pad by Eli Lilly operators. On 06-24-2005 outside carrier Liquid Transport Corporation came in to get trailer #TT321R67 for delivery to Eli Lilly and Company, Clinton Laboratories, Clinton, IN for incineration of the liquid waste . Liquid Transport hooked up to tanker #TT321R67 and  proceeded toward the Tippecanoe Laboratories exit gate (Security Headquarters). Prior to the tanker exiting the plant site, two Eli Lilly employees noticed the tanker dripping and smelled a strong solvent smell as the truck passed them. The two Eli Lilly employees notified Tippecanoe Laboratories Security of their observations. Investigation by Tippecanoe Laboratories Security discovered that the man-way dome had not been fastened down after loading, allowing the tanker contents to spill out onto the plant site roadway.    The man way dome was then secured tightly by the Liquid Transport driver and was then checked by Eli Lilly personnel. Eli  Lilly personnel then spread absorbent material on the small amount (less than 2 liters) of waste that had spilled onto the plant site roadway. The exterior of the cargo tank was checked for any remaining residue and the tanker was declared free of residue by Tippecanoe Laboratories Environmental personnel. Liquid Transport was then cleared for departure by Tippecanoe Laboratories Hazardous Material Regulations Specialist to deliver the cargo tanker to Eli Lilly, Clinton Laboratories in Clinton, IN. The absorbent material was subsequently collected and drummed for incineration on site.    Carrier information:    Liquid Transport Corporation  8470 Allison Point Boulevard, Suite 400  Indianapolis, Indiana 46250    Federal DOT ID Number 070892    Hazmat Registration Number 052303 550 010LN
column169: Eli Lilly and Company, Tippecanoe Laboratories re-enforced DOT training and HAZMAT loading and unloading procedures with the appropriate operators to ensure that vessel closures are securely closed immediately following loading or unloading.  Procedures will be reviewed and revised, if needed, to include verbiage explaining that closure gaskets are to be correctly seated and all screw type closure devices are tool tightened.  Liquid Transport Corp. has been contacted to remind all drivers that it is their responsibility per DOT regulations to ensure closures are secure before moving the cargo tank.

column168: THE DRIVER OF A TRACTOR-TRAILER OPERATED BY KLLM TRANSPORTATION, WHILE PERFORMING ROUTINE TRAILER INSPECTION, OBSERVED PAINT LEAKING FROM THE REAR OF THE TRAILER.  THE TRAILER CONTAINED 76 DRUMS OF PAINT UN 1263.  THE DRIVER THEN NOTIFIED HIS DISPATCH.  ON JUNE 21, 2005 AT APPROXIMATELY 4:00 A.M., MR. DON JOHNSON WITH KLLM TRANSPORTATION SERVICES RETAINED CURA EMERGENCY SERVICES (CES) TO MANAGE ENVIRONMENTAL CLEANUP OPERATIONS.  THE CES INCIDENT MANAGER THEN CONTACTED THE DRIVER AND OBTAINED ADDITIONAL SITE INFORMATION.  BASED ON THE AVAILABLE INFORMATION, THE CES INCIDENT MANAGER CONTACTED ENVIRSOLVE LOCATED IN ALBUQUERQUE, NEW MEXICO TO INITIATE CORRECTIVE ACTIONS.  THE CREW WITH ENVIROSOLVE ARRIVED ONSITE AND ENTERED THE SUBJECT TRAILER.  RESPONSE PERSONNEL HAD TO OFFLOAD SEVERAL DRUMS IN ORDER TO GAIN ACESS TO THE LEAKING DRUM.  ONCE THE LEAKING DRUM WAS IDENTIFIED IT WAS PLACED INTO A 95 GALLON OVERPACK.  RESPONSE PERSONNEL THEN APPLIED ABSORBENT MATERIAL ONTO THE TRAILER FLOOR IN ORDER TO ABSORB AND CONTAIN THE SPILLED PAINT.  THE SPENT ABSORBENT WAS THEN COLLECTED AND PLACED INTO A DRUM FOR PROPER DISPOSAL.
BOX OF LIQUID LEAKING WHEN UNLOADING FREIGHT.  LIQUID CLEANED UP AND BOX THEN TO H/M AREA ON DOCK.  ONE BOTTLE @ 67.6 OZ = N3-R FIXER REPLENISHER

column168: BNSF SWITCHMAN REPORTED NATX 38339 LEAKING PRODUCT FROM AROUND THE PROTECTIVE HOUSING COVER AREA DURING TANK CAR'S MOVEMENT IN THE RAILYARD.  NATX 38339 WAS ISOLATED IN THE RAILYARD.  BNSF RESPONDER REPORTED THAT THE VALVE HOUSING PLATE FLANGE HAD ALL 12 OF ITS FLANGE BOLTS LOOSE WITH TWO OF THESE BOLTS MISSING THEIR NUTS.  THIS FLANGE PLATE HAD THE LIQUID EDUCTION AND VAPOR LINES TO ATOP IT.  THE BNSF RESPONDER ALSO NOTICED THAT PART OF THE FLANGE PLATE GASKET WAS OUTSIDE THE PLATE FLANGE LIP AREA.  CONSIGNEE CONTRACT RESPONDERS ARRIVED TO SECURE THE FLANGE BOLTS AND APPLY A GASKET SEALANT (READI-SEAL) TO THE DETERIORATED PORTIONS OF THE FLANGE GASKET.  REPAIRS AND SECUREMENT WERE COMPLETED AROUND NOON ON 6/07/05; AND NATX 38339 WAS RELEASED TO PROCEED TO ITS DESTINATION LATER THAT DAY AFTER NO FURTHER PRODUCT RELEASE EVIDENT DURING ITS MOVEMENT IN THE RAILYARD.  ALL SPILLAGE EVAPORATED AND NO PRODUCT WAS REPORTED TO IMPACT THE GROUND.

BNSF RESPONDER REPORTED THAT THE FRANGIBLE DISC HAD RUPTURED AND WITH ADVICE FROM THE SHIPPER, THE RESPONDER WAS ABLE TO LOCATE THE SPARE FRANGIBLE DISC ON THIS TANK CAR.  RESPONDER REPLACED THE BLOWN FRANGIBLE DISC WITH THE REPLACEMENT DISC.  SPILLAGE ON THE SIDE SHELL DRIED AND NO PRODUCT WAS REPORTED IMPACTING THE GROUND.  AFTER THE REPLACEMENT FRANGIBLE DISC WAS INSTALLED, NO FURTHER PRODUCT RELEASE WAS EVIDENT IN SUBSEQUENT YARD MOVEMENTS OF UTLX 200526.

column168: BNSF TRAIN CREW SWITCHING IN RAILYARD, REPORTED PRODUCT ODOR EMANATING FROM UTLX 204544.  CREW ALSO REPORTED FRESH LIQUID PRODUCT ON THE SIDE SHELL THAT WAS EVAPORATING.  UTLX 204544 WAS CORDONED OFF IN RAILYARD.  BNSF CONTRACT RESPONDERS WITH AIR MONITORING EQUIPMENT APPROACHED UTLX 204544.  SEAL #087496 WAS REMOVED FROM PROTECTIVE HOUSING COVER.  RESPONDERS FOUND THE 2 INCH CLOSURE PLUG TO THE LIQUID LINE VALVE ONLY HAD TIGHT AND THIS VALVES OPERATING HANDLE APPROXIMATELY 1/4 TURN OPEN.  RESPONDERS CLOSED VALVE AND TOOL TIGHTENED THE CLOSURE PLUG, ENDING FURTHER PRODUCT RELEASE BY 1820 HRS. CDT.  ABSORBENT PADS WERE USED TO CLEAN VALVE BODY AND VICINITY.  RESPONDERS THEN PROCEEDED TO CHECK OTHER VALVES AND FITTINGS FOR SECUREMENT, FINDING NO OTHER LEAK SOURCES.  ALTHOUGH, THE ONE INCH CLOSURE PLUG ON THE VAPOR VALVE WAS FOUND TO BE ONLY HAND TIGHT AND THIS PLUG WAS TOOL TIGHTENED.  ALL SPILLAGE ON TANK SHELL EVAPORATED AND NO PRODUCT SPILLAGE WAS REPORTED IMPACTING GROUND.  TWO BNSF CREW MEMBERS WHOM DISCOVERED THE UTLX 204544 PRODUCT RELEASE COMPLAINED OF CHEMICAL INHALATION EXPOSURE AND THEY WERE TAKEN TO THE LOCAL HOSPITAL.  BOTH EMPLOYEES WERE DECONTAMINATED PER HOSPITAL PROTOCOL AND EXAMINED.  ONE EMPLOYEE WAS GIVEN TYLENOL #3 FOR A HEADACHE COMPLAINT.  THE OTHER EMPLOYEE RECEIVED AN UNKNOWN PRESCRIPTIVE INJECTION FOR A HEADACHE AND NAUSEA COMPLAINT.  BOTH EMPLOYEE'S PULMONARY FUNCTION EXAMS WERE NORMAL AND BOTH WERE RELEASED TO RETURN TO NON-RESTRICTED DUTY WITH NO LOST WORK DAYS REPORTED.

column168: Driver was unloading product from rail car to trailer when he noticed a small leak from the valve packing on the "A" side valve that he was using to unload.  He closed valve and bled down the connections.  Driver tired to tighten packing nut, but was unable to obtain adequate leverage to do so.  Driver contacted corporate office for further instructions.  Driver was instructed to resume unloading using the "B" valve.  “B” valve packing also leaked slightly.  Driver tightened packing nut and stopped leak.  Once unloading was complete, driver tried tightening packing nut on the "A" valve and was successful.  Driver verified that neither valve leaked.  No evacuations were made, no injuries reported, and no complaints of off-site odor were recorded.  Less than 1 pound of vapor was estimated to have been released.

Upon looking at the can a small drip appeared to be emanating from a weld on the bottom of the UN spec container.  Weld seemed to have failed.  Jeff Deitz local faa HAZMAT agent was notified.  He came to warehouse and began an investigation.  The 1 or two ounces that leaked in A/C were cleaned up and pilot and maintenance notified.

column58: Pressure Relief Valve or Device - Non-Reclosing
column168: Employee- Shepherd Williams was making a propane delivery when the relief valve opened on the ASME tank that he was filling. He had loaded 300 gallon to the 500 gallon tank and the relief valve failed and opened due to age.    The employee sustained minor freeze burns to his face and his right bicep. He was treated and no lost work time.
column169: We view this as a fluke situation- We will continue to monitor valves for their operation.
column172: Container, no description given (do not use if at all possible)

column58: Fusible Pressure Relief Device or Element
column168: At approximately 13:20:00 hours, TSUI driver, Eduardo Perdomo, during the transportation of two multi-unit tank car tanks on a flatbed trailer, detected a chlorine odor with his sense of smell.  He drove the vehicle to a safe location (intersection of Alico Road, West of I-75 in western Florida)and notified the shipper, Allied Universal Corp. of Medley, FL. He spoke to the Branch Manager, Bernie Thompson.  Mr. Thompson was unable to respond to the scene immediately to mitigate any chlorine release from the tank as he and his responders were three hours from the scene.  Mr. Thompson called 911.  The San Carlos Fire Department responded to the scene at 14:00:00 hours.  The public responders determined a small vapor release from the fusible plug of one chlorine multi unit tank car tank. Area of leak could not be seen by human eye, no hole or other damage visible.  The responders evacuated the Hess Gas Station (number of people evacuated unknown), and proceeded to mitigate the release of chlorine vapor by applying the Chlorine Institute Emergency B Kit device.  Once the kit was securely in place and the release terminated, the TSUI driver was released from the scene at 16:00:00 hours to return to the Allied Medley, Florida facility.  At the facility, the container was to be unloaded of its product and inspected.
column169: Multi unit tank car tank inspected at the shipper's facility.  Fusible plug thread wear/deterioration determined to be the cause of the incident.  Employees tasked with filling the multi unit tank car tanks retrained on thread inspection and container inspection per Chlorine Institute Pamphlet 17 as well as company operating policy for filling containers.

column168: DATE TIME AND PLACE:  THIS LOSS OCCURRED ON JUNE 8, 2005 AT APPROXIMATELY 2:45 A.M. LOCATED AT THE VALLEY NATIONAL GASES FACILITY, 61504 SOUTH GATE ROAD, CAMBRIDGE, OHIO.  DESCRIPTION OF THE INCIDENT: THE INSURED DRIVER, DICK FLOWERS, WAS MAKING A PROPANE DELIVERY AT THE ABOVE LOCATION, WHEN DURING THE TRANSFERRING OF PROPANE FROM THE INSURED'S UNIT TO THE FACILITY'S STATIONARY TANK, A LEAK LOCATED IN THE MAIN TANK LINE (VALVE) ALLOWED THE ESCAPE OF GAS.  INSURED:  THE INSURED AS IT APPEARS ON THE POLICY IS MCLIVAINE TRUCKING INC OF 7556 CLEVELAND ROAD IN WOOSTER, OHIO 44691.  UPON OUR ARRIVAL AT THE SCENE, WE MET WITH TOM MICELI, VICE PRESIDENT OF SAFETY AND THE DRIVER, DICK FLOWERS.  MR. FLOWERS STATED THAT HE ARRIVED AT THE FACILITY DURING THE MORNING HOURS, 2:30-3:45 A.M.  THE DRIVER STATED THAT HE HAS MADE DELIVERIES BY HIMSELF TO THIS LOCATION FOR A NUMBER OF YEARS----A TWENTY-EIGHT YEAR VETERAN AND FAMILIAR WITH PROCEDURES.  MR. FLOWERS STATED THAT HE INTENDED TO DELIVER TEN THOUSAND GALLONS OF PROPANE INTO A THIRTY THOUSAND GALLON HOLDING TANK.  PRIOR TO FILLING, MR. FLOWERS CHECKED THE LEVELS IN THE CLAIMANT'S HOLDING TANK, WHICH WAS REGISTERING 91% EMPTY.  THIS INDICATED THAT THE DELIVERY WOULD HOLD DUE TO THE DEBRIS IN VALVE SEAT ON CUSTOMERS LINE.  MR. FLOWERS CONFIRMED CHECKING ALL VALVE ON HIS TRUCK, AND THE STATIONARY TANK PRIOR TO HOOKING THE FILLER HOSE TO THE TANK, THEN PUMPING.  AS SOON AS PUMPING WAS INITIATED, MR. FLOWERS STATED THAT HE NOTICED THE GAS LEAKING AND SHUT OFF HIS EQUIPMENT IN ADDITION TO ATTEMPTING TO SHUT OFF THE VALVES ON THE CONNECTING HOSE AND TANK.  THE BOTTOM VALVE ON THE TANK COULD NOT BE CLOSED.  MR. FLOWERS IMMEDIATELY LEFT THE AREA AND CALLED 911 FOR THE PROPER RESPONSE.  THE LEAK WAS THEN REPORTED TO HIS TERMINAL.  WITNESS: NONE
column169: MANDATORY INSPECTION REQUIREMENTS FOR ALL LPC STORAGE TANK & VALVES.

column168: THIS SHIPPER OFFERED THESE PACKAGES AS UN 1719 ON 6/20/05.  THE FOUR BOXES WERE REFUSED FOR SHIPPING ERRORS ON THE SHIPPING PAPERS AND/OR PACKAGE MARKINGS & LABELING.  THE FREIGHT WAS RETURNED TO THE SHIPPER ON 6/21/05.  SUBSEQUENTLY AND LATER ON 6/21/05, FEDEX EXPRESS RECEIVED A REQUEST TO PICK FOUR PACKAGES FROM THE SHIPPER.  WE ACCEPTED FOUR, PLAIN BROWN BOXES FROM THE SHIPPER'S LOCATION.  THE OFFERING PARTY FAILED TO MARK, LABEL, OR OFFER SHIPPING PAPERS WITH THE SHIPMENT.  WHEN THE FREIGHT ARRIVED AT THE FEDEX STATION IN CARTERSVILLE, GA THE LOCAL DANGEROUS GOODS SPECIALIST CALLED TO ADVISE ON THE SITUATION.  I ASKED THEM TO OPEN THE BOXES.  UPON DOING SO WE FOUND AN MSDS THAT REFLECTED THAT CONTENTS WERE CAUSTIC ALKAHLI LIQUID, N.O.S.  THE FAA IN ATL WAS NOTIFIED, I SPOKE TO SA WYLIE KILPATRICK.  THE FREIGHT IS BEING HELD PENDING AN FAA INSPECTION.  FEDEX EXPRESS HAS EMBARGOED ALL BOX FREIGHT FROM THIS SHIPPER UNTIL FURTHER NOTICE.

column42: AEROSOLS, FLAMMABLE, (EACH NOT EXCEEDING 1 L CAPACITY)
column168: WHEN THE PACKAGE WAS FOUND LEAKING, WE SAW 3 AEROSOL CANS HAD LOST THEIR CAPS.  WE SUSPECT THAT THE BOX WAS INVERTED AT SOME POINT, ALLOWING THE BUTTONS ON THE CANS TO BE DEPRESSED, ALLOWING THE HAIR SPRAY TO ESCAPE.  THERE WERE NO MARKINGS, LABELING, SHIPPING PAPERS OR OTHER INDICATORS TO LEAD US TO BELIEVE THE CONTENTS WERE REGULATED.  THE FAA WAS NOTIFIED, I SPOKE TO SA DREW STABALA.  THE FREIGHT WAS HELD PENDING AN FAA INSPECTION.

AS THE BOX WAS BEING UNLOADED FROM A FEDEX TRUCK, IT WAS DROPPED ON TO A CEMENT FLOOR.  THE OR AN INNER GLASS BOTTLE CRACKED, ALLOWING THE CONTENTS TO ESCAPE.  THE BOTTLE WAS PROTECT BY AN ABSORBENT MATERIAL AND A PLASTIC BARRIER BAG.  PACKING INSTRUCTION 612 WAS IDENTIFIED ON THE SHIPPER'S DECLARATION (SD).  PI 612 ALLOWS FOR UP TO 2.5 LITRES PER GLASS INNER PACKAGE.  AS THERE WAS 16 LITRES DECLARED ON THE SD, THE BOX WASN'T LARGE ENOUGH TO ACCOMODATE EIGHT PLUS INNER CONTAINERS AT 2.5 LITRES.  IT IS MY BELIEF THAT THE SHIPPER HAD FEW INNER CONTAINERS THAT THE EIGHT PLUS WITH A GREAT CAPACITY THAN 2.5 LITRES.  I SPOKE WITH THE SHIPPER AND REQUESTED TRAINING RECORDS, PACKAGE TEST RESULTS AND A COPY OF THE SD.  MY REQUEST, WAS DENIED.  AS THIS WAS AN RQ AND I BELIEVED THE SPILL TO MEET/EXCEED THE RQ, THE NATIONAL RESPONSE CENTER WAS NOTIFIED.  SUBSEQUENTLY I WAS CONTACTED BY TOM LASSEIGNE FROM THE NTSB.  THE FAA WAS ALSO NOTIFIED I SPOKE TO SA STEVE JOSEPH AND SA PETER SCHUROTT.  THE FREIGHT HAS SINCE BEEN INSPECTED BY THE FAA.  ONCE THE FREIGHT IS RELEASED THE SHIPPER WILL BE ABLE TO RECOVER THEIR FREIGHT.

column168: AT 1500HRS ON 6-9-05, FRANK LERCH, MANAGER CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY WAS CONTACTED BY MECHANICAL MANAGER RONNIE LEWIS. WHO ADVISED TANK CAR GATX 300460 LOCATED IN BOWL TRACK 14, SETTEGAST YARD WAS LEAKING.  MGR. LERCH RESPONDED, AND CONTACTED THE RMCC TO MAKE SHIPPER NOTIFICATION VIA CHEMTREC.  ON ARRIVAL AT THE NORTHEAST LEAD SWITCH SHANTY, MGR. LERCH SPOKE TO LOCAL TRAIN PERSONNEL, WHO INDICATED THAT WHILE SWITCHING THE CAR, THEY NOTED A SMALL AMOUNT OF PRODUCT HAD LEAKED FROM THE TOP OF THE CAR.  WHILE IN THE IMMEDIATE AREA, MGR. LERCH DETECTED A SLIGHT RESIDUAL ODOR OF THE SPILLED PRODUCT.  HOWEVER, THERE WAS NO PRODUCT IN THE AREA OR ON THE GROUND, AS IT EVAPORATED UPON CONTACT WITH THE ATMOSPHERE.  AFTER SECURING BOWL, TRACK 14, MGR. LERCH INSPECTED THE CAR, WHICH WAS ISOLATED AND LOCATED MIDWAY DOWN THE TRACK.  INSPECTION NOTED THE FOLLOWING EXCEPTIONS: SIX OF SIX MANWAY SWING BOLTS WERE IN POSITION, AND NOT SECURED WRENCH TIGHT.  THE TWO INCH LIQUID VALVE WAS NOTED TO BE CLOSED, HOWEVER WHERE IT ATTACHES TO THE EDUCTION LINE NIPPLE, IT WAS FOUND TO BE LOOSE TURN.  ADDITIONALLY, THE AIR VALVE PLUG WAS IN POSITION, FINGER TIGHT, WITH THE VALVE NOTED TO BE IN THE CLOSED. POSITION.  AFTER CORRECTING ALL NOTED EXCEPTIONS, THE CAR WAS DETERMINED TO BE SECURED, AND WAS RELEASED FOR TRANSPORTATION.  THERE WAS NO CLEAN-UP OF THE CAR REQUIRED, AS THERE WAS NO PRODUCT REMAINING ON THE CAR DUE TO PROTECT EVAPORATION.  THERE WAS HOWEVER, A SLIGHT RESIDUAL ODOR ON THE CAR FROM THE RELEASED PRODUCT WHICH WOULD DISSIPATE.  AT 1630HRS AFTER SECURING THE CAR, MGR. LERCH CLEARED THE AREA.  AT 2025HRS, MGR. LERCH WAS CONTACTED BY MANGER TERMINAL OPERATIONS, PAUL DAY.  HE INDICATED THAT YARD PERSONNEL REPORTED THEY SUSPECTED THE CAR WAS STILL LEAKIND DUE TO THE ODOR THEY COULD SMELL.  MGR. LERCH ADVISED MR. DAY IT WAS A RESIDUAL ODOR THAT THEY WERE SMELLING, AND THAT IT WAS NOT HARMFUL, AND WOULD DISSIPATE.  AT 2100HRS MGR. LERCH WAS CONTACTED MR. DAY WHO REPORTED 2 EMPLOYEES WERE COMPLAINING OF IRRITATED THROATS, TINGLING SKIN AND WATERY EYES DUE TO THE ODOR.  MGR. LERCH IMMEDIATELY RESPONDED, CONTACTED THE SHIPPER, AND MADE ARRANGEMENTS TO APPLY AN INDUSTRIAL DEODORIZER IN THE AFFECTED AREA.  SEALS PROTECTING: ORIGINAL COMBINATION HOUSING - TEXMARK 13348, REPLACED BY UPRR CTS-0008773; ORIGINAL MANWAY COVER TEXMARK-13347, REPLACED BY UPRR CTS-0008774.  PART III - PACKING INFORMATION: QUESTION 25. (CONTINUTED): 3. WHAT FAILED 134 152  HOW FAILED: 308  CAUSES OF FAILURE: 526

ROBERT BAVIER, MANAGER OF CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION AND SAFETY, WAS NOTIFIED AND ADVISED UNITED PUMPING SERVICES WAS EN ROUTE FOR REMEDIATION. RAPHAEL, SUPERVISOR RAMP RAIL TERMINAL SERVICE, REPORTED CONTAINER BSIU202869, WAS LEAKING PRODUCT ON THE GROUND, AND HE HAD ALREADY PLACED A CHEMICAL SPILL KIT DOWN.  VERN LIBBY, SENIOR SPECIAL AGENT, WAS NOTIFIED AND RESPONDED.  ALL NECESSARY STATE NOTIFICATIONS WERE MADE.  AT 11:18 PM, SAHM LIBBY ADVISED THAT THE CONTAINER HAD BEEN ISOLATED WITH ABSORBENT PADS, CONES, AND A BURM AROUND THE LEAK CONTAINER.  CONTAINER SEAL KELLER SEALS 6594854 WAS REMOVED AND DOOR OPENED.  IMMEDIATELY NOTED INSUFFICIENT BLOCKING AND BRACING.  AAR CORDSTRAPS WERE USED IN THE DOORWAY AND CARDBOARD WAS USED TO SEPARATE THE STACKED DRUMS.  LIBBY CONTACTED KEVIN RUNNELS, CHEMTREC, WHO ASSIGNED CHEMTRC CASE NUMBER 0604/2005-058.  RUNNELS PLACED LIBBY IN CONTACT WITH KYLE NELSON, DOW CORNING CARROLLTON, KY.  NEILSON CONTRACTED DIRECTLY WITH JASON POTTS, NRC ENVIRONMENTAL TO WORK THIS INCIDENT.  NIELSON ALSO PROVIDED AN MSDS FOR THE PRODUCT.  THE PRODUCT WAS IDENTIFIED AS XIAMETER PMX-0110.  UNLOADING THE CONTAINER, 35 OF THE TOP 40 DRUMS WERE NOTED WITH CHIME RUB.  THREE OF THESE DRUMS HAD RUBBED THROUGH RESULTING IN A LOSS OF APPROXIMATELY 135 GALLONS OF PRODUCT BETWEEN ORIGIN AND SEATTLE, WA.  THE THREE OVERPACKED LEAKERS AND THE REMAINING 32 DRUMS WITH CHIME RUB WERE RELOADED INTO CONTAINER BSIU 202869, BLOCKED AND BRACED, SEALED UP S-141637 AND RETURNED TO DOW CORNING CARROLLTON, KY., FOR THEIR HANDLING.  THE REMAINING 45 INTACT DRUMS WERE LOADED INTO CONTAINER FSCU 926829, BLOCKED AND BRACED, SEALED UP S-141648 AND RELEASED FOR DELIVERY TO DESTINATION.

column168: ON WEDNESDAY, JUNE 15TH CARLISLE FINISHING COMPANY CONTACTED CSX TRANSPORTATION FOR ADVICE AND ASSISTANCE WITH TANK CAR UCLX16382 (LOAD - SODIUM HYDROXIDE) WHICH WAS DRIPPING PRODUCT INSIDE THEIR FACILITY. THE SHIPPER, VULCAN CHEMICALS (JOHN BURCHETT 316-529-7497) WAS ADVISED OF THE INCIDENT AND HAS ARRANGED TO WAYBILL THE CAR BACK TO THEIR FACILITY IN GEISMAR, LA, FOR INSPECTION / REPAIR.  NOTE: CSX TRANSPORTATION PLACED THE TANK CAR ISNIDE THE FACILITY ON JUNE 12TH AT 1140 HOURS.

SEKAVEC INSPECTED THE CAR AND OBSERVED THE MANWAY GASKET APPEARED TO BE IN POOR CONDITION PRIOR TO OPENING THE MANWAY COVER.  UPON OPENING THE COVER, THE GASKET SEPARATED AND FELL INTO THE TANK CAR.  MR. SEKAVEC CLEANED THE MANWAY NOZZLE AND COVER AND INSTALLED A NEW GASKET FROM GORE-TX GASKET MATERIAL.  AFTER RESECURING THE MANWAY, MR. SEKAVEC REQUESTED A YARD JOB JOSTLE THE CAR BACK AND FORTH TO VERIFY THAT THERE WERE NO LEAKS FROM THE NEWLY INSTALLED GASKET.  THE CAR WAS THEN RELEASED TO CONTINUE IN TRANSPORTATION.  THERE WAS NO REMEDIATION PLANNED FOR THE SMALL AMOUNT OF MATERIAL THAT REACHED THE BALLAST AS IT HAD ALREADY EVAPORATED, LEAVING NO RESIDUE OR MATERIAL TO BE REMOVED.  NO OTHER ENVIRONMENTAL IMPACT IS EXPECTED FROM THIS RELEASE.

MTO SLATT FURTHER STATED THE TANKCAR WAS PLACED ON TRACK 405 NEXT TO CX490.  RYAN SCHMALL, SENIOR SPECIAL AGENT, AND DEAN COOPER, MANAGER, CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY, WERE NOTIFIED.  MR. COOPER RESPONDED.  ALL NECESSARY STATE NOTIFICATIONS WERE MADE.  AT 11:00PM, MANAGER COOPER REPORTED HE WOULD INSPECT THE TANKCAR UPON THE ARRIVAL OF A PHILLIPS SERVICES CONTRACTOR.  MR. COOPER ADVISED HE HAD DEVELOPED INFORMATION THAT AN EMPLOYEE, WHO WAS STANDING NEAR THE TANKCAR DURING THE SWITCHING OPERATION, RECEIVED A LIGHT MISTING OF THE PRODUCT FROM THE TANK CAR WHEN THE PRODUCT SPLASHED OUT.  RMCC CONTACTED MTO SLATT, WHO ADVISED THE EMPLOYEE WAS TAKEN TO THE YARD OFFICE, DISROBED AND BATHED AS A PRECAUTION FROM THE EXPOSURE.  MTO SLATT CONFIRMED THE EMPLOYEE HAD PRODUCT ON HIS CLOTHING AND MR. COOPER INSTRUCTED THE EMPLOYEE BE ADVISED TO DISPOSE OF THE CLOTHING.  MR. SLATT STATED THE EMPLOYEE DID NOT SEEK MEDICAL TREATMENT.  AT 12:17AM, MANAGER COOPER REPORTED THE FRANGIBLE DISC IN THE SAFETY VENT WAS DAMAGED, POSSIBLY FROM ROUGH HANDLING OF THE TANKCAR DURING SWITCHING OPERATIONS, AND THE DISC HAD BEEN REPLACED WITH A LIKE TYPE.  THE FLIP BACK ALUMINUM COVER CAP FOR THE SAFETY VENT HAD THE PIN TAB TORN OFF DURING THE RELEASE, WHICH WILL REQUIRE REPAIR.  THE REMAINING VALVES AND FITTINGS WERE INSPECTED AND FOUND TO BE SECURE.  MANAGER COOPER STATED THE RESIDUE ON THE TOP OF THE TANKCAR WOULD BE CLEANED OFF MONDAY MORNING, 6/13/2005, BY PHILLIPS, THE RAILROADS HAZMAT CONTRACTOR.  MANAGER COOPER REQUESTED RMCC ENSURE THE SHIPPER WAS NOTIFIED FOR FOLLOW UP REPAIRS AT THE LATER DATE.  RON MILLER, CHEMTREC, WAS UPDATED AND ADVISED HE WOULD RELAY THE INFORMATION TO THE SHIPPER.  AT 01:18AM, MANAGER COOPER REPORTED WHILE CLEANING THE TOOLS AND ORIGINAL FRANGIBLE DISC, IT WAS DISCOVERED THE DAMAGED DISC WAS A 60 POUND DISC, AND A 165 POUND DISC WAS REQUIRED FOR THE TANKCAR SAFETY VENT.  MR. COOPER ADVISED HE CONTACTED RYAN SCHMALL, SENIOR SPECIAL AGENT, AND RELINQUISHED THE DISC TO HIM FOR STORAGE IN LOCAL EVIDENCE LOCKER.

PART TIME SUPERVISOR ROBERT BECERRA WAS TOLD THERE WORE A LEAKING HAZMAT PACKAGE ON BLUE BELT.  HE STOPPED BELT AND BECAUSE HE IS ALSO A RESPONDER - HE WENT AND GOT HAZ MAT CERT SPILL TRAY & PUT ON THE PROPER PPE AND FOLLOWED THE DECISION TREE & RESPONSE SHEET - CLEANED UP & REMOVED SPILL TO HAZMAT AREA - WHERE OTHER RESPONDER JOLENNE THOMAS FINISHED AND PROCESSED THE DAMAGE THRU THE DMP.
column169: FOR SHIPPER NEEDS TO BE AWARE TO MAKE SURE ALL CAPS ARE TIGHTENED ON CONTAINERS - ONE WAS COMPLETELY OFF OF 1 OF THE CANS.

column168: OTHER MOTORISTS TRAVELING OBSERVED THE DRIVER WESTBOUND ON IH-20 NEAR COLORADO CITY, TEXAS.  SPEED WAS ESTIMATED AT APPROXIMATELY 68 TO 70 MPH.  IMMEDIATELY AFTER PASSING A CAR WITH TWO OCCUPANTS, THE TRUCK MADE A SUDDEN RIGHT HAND MOVEMENT, CROSSED IN FRONT OF THE CAR, HIT A STEEL GUARDRAIL, THEN HIT THE CONCRETE ABUTMENT OF AN OVERPASS, TRAVELED ACROSS THE BRIDGE RAILING, WENT OVER THE SIDE OF THE OVERPASS, DRIVING THE TRACTOR AND TRAILER INTO THE CONCRETE SURROUNDING THE AREA BELOW THE OVERPASS.  THE TRACTOR WAS TOTALLY DESTROYED.  THE DRIVER WAS DISMEMBERED AND THROWN FROM WHAT WAS LEFT OF THE TRACTOR CAB.  THE TRACTOR AND TRAILER FELL ABOUT 30 FEET FROM THE TOP OF THE BRIDGE TO THE CONCRETE AREA BELOW THE BRIDGE.  THE TRAILER TOOK A DIRECT HIT ON THE FRONT NOSE AND WAS CRUSHED.  THE LEAK RESULTED FROM THE INNER AND OUTER TANK BEING CRUSHED.  THE TRAILER DID NOT RIP OPEN.  THE METAL INSIDE THE INNER VESSEL WAS ONLY SLIGHTLY TORN AND AS A RESULT TOOK QUITE A WHILE TO DISPERSE THE PRODUCT, LIQUID NITROGEN.  THE RELEASE CONTINUED FOR APPROXIMATELY 6 1/2 HOURS.  THE COUNTY JUDGE ORDERED AN AUTOPSY.  THE RESULTS WILL NOT BE READY FOR APPROXIMATELY 3 MONTHS PER THE DALLAS COUNT MEDICAL EXAMINERS OFFICE.  THE INVESTIGATING OFFICER, JEREMY USENER AND A TEXAS WEIGHTS AND MEASURES OFFICER JOHNSON EXAMINED BOTH THE TRACTOR AND TRAILER.  ALSO MEMBERS OF THE CARRIER PARTICIPATED IN THE VEHICLE EXAMINATION.  NO APPARENT MECHANICAL DEFECTS WERE FOUND IN EITHER VEHICLE.  THE INVESTIGATING OFFICER, JEREMY USENER, RELAYED MOST OF THE INFORMATION IN THIS REPORT TO MYSELF.  I HAD ATTACHED PICTURES TO HELP UNDERSTAND HOW THE CARGO TANK WAS DAMAGED.  OVERALL, I PERSONALLY BELIEVE THAT THE CARGO TANK HELD UP EXCEPTIONALLY WELL CONSIDERING THE SEVERITY OF THE IMPACT.  THE PRODUCT WAS NITROGEN, REFRIGERATED LIQUID.  THE PRODUCT WAS DISPERSED BACK INTO THE ATMOSPHERE.
