column62: Defective Component or Device; Corrosion - Interior
column168: Shortly after 7:00 pm on June 6, 2005, a shipment arrived at Fleurchem’s site at 33 Sprague Avenue in Middletown, New York. George Gluck, Fleurchem’s CEO, together with Louis Mercun, Fleurchem’s Director of Operations, opened the cargo trailer  and noticed an immediate odor. Fleurchem had been expecting a shipment of 80 drums of acetaldehyde but Mr. Gluck noticed that the containers had no hazardous markings identifying this shipment as a hazardous material shipment. Although he noticed an odor, he did not see any liquid or other visual sign of a release.. They used an explosive- level meter and determined, based on the lower explosive limit (LEL) reading, that they should leave the back of the cargo trailer door slightly open overnight in the secure area of Fleurchem’s gated site and re-check the LEL level in the morning.  The next morning the LEL level was normal and there was no odor. An inspection revealed a tiny pinhole on the seam of one drum approximately 6” from its top. The pinhole appeared to have sealed itself, as no tI.irther vapor was being dispersed. The measurement of the remaining acetaldehyde indicated that 12 kilos had been released from the drum. There was no bulging or noticeable defect in any of the other special pressurized drums.
column169: Fleurchem identified two areas of concern in connection with this incident. .First, there was the lack of hazardous identification markings in connection with this shipment. Second, one of the containers transporting the materials appeared to be defective.  Fleurchem notified each involved party (both in China and here) of the problems with this shipment and the need (1) to ensure compliance with both IMDG and USDOT hazardous materials codes and regulations, and (2) when possible, to conduct appropriate inspections of hazardous materials containers.

column168: Agnum U.S. Inc.  West Sacramento Nitrogen Operations  Addendum to Form DOT F 5800.1  Ammonia Release of June 8, 2005  Part VI- Description of Events and Release  A Pressure Safety Valve (PSV) on a ammonia trailer operated by Button Transportation opened and released ammonia to the atmosphere. The truck/trailer was loading at Rack 3 at the Agrium, West Sacramento facility at the time of the incident. Statements from various Plant personnel were taken by John Killey (EH&S Supervisor). There were at ihe time of the incident two ammonia loading control systems, the older using Brooks meters and at the time, only on Racks 3 & 4, and the newer Digital Control System (DCS) controlling Racks 1 & 2. The Brooks meters require the input of the target net weight of ammonia and the DCS requires target gross weight. The operator was busy with several trucks at the time and erroneously keyed in a gross weight to an instrument that required a net weight approximately 40,000 lbs less. The system attempted to deliver an excess amount of ammonia to the truck. As the tank filled beyond it’s intended capacity, the pressure rose rapidly in the reduced head space slowing the fill-rate and the PSV opened. Shift personnel responded to the release by stopping the loading and moving persons in the area. Administration personnel were made aware of the release and subsequently also responded.  Regulatory and neighbor notifications were made by Plant personnel. No injuries or property damage occurred.  It was subsequently calculated by engineering support personnel that approximately 48 lbs of ammonia in vapor form were released to the atmosphere. A review of digital recordings of the security cameras showed the incident from the camera on the urea warehouse and that the cloud did not visibly migrate off site.  Causes  1. Incorrect load number input.  2. Two systems operable at the same time.  3. Failure to check/monitor/correct input error or monitor loading process.  4. Failure to communicate/coordinate — did not ask for help as task load increased.  Part VII- Actions Taken to Prevent Recurrence  1. Provide training to cover:  i. At the truck racks, if there is a problem, initiate the stop then evaluate the problem. “Stop then think”.  ii. For scale-house personnel; emphasizing the need to be in the scale house when ammonia loading is taking place and not to attempt to deal with too many trucks simultaneously.
